nl: Show me the state and license plate format for the 3 most recent series of plates that have a slogan and use either a blue-on-white or black-on-white color scheme.
sql:
SELECT
  `State/territory`,
  `Format`
FROM
  `table_1_1000181_1`
WHERE
  `Text/background colour` IN (`'blue/white'`, `'black/white'`)
  AND `Notes` NOT LIKE `'%No slogan%'`
ORDER BY
  `Current series` DESC
LIMIT
  3;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col2 FROM `table_1_1000181_1` WHERE col1 IN ('blue/white', 'black/white') AND col5 NOT LIKE '%No slogan%' ORDER BY col4 DESC;
reasoning: This question rephrases the query as a command, using more conversational language. It combines the sorting and limit clauses into the more natural concept of '3 most recent series'. The color and slogan conditions are presented as essential characteristics of the plates being sought.

nl: If we model a pterosaur with the mass of the heaviest helicopter on this list, what theoretical wing area would it need if we assume it has a lift efficiency equivalent to the lowest disk loading value among these aircraft?
sql:
SELECT (
  SELECT CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, `(`) + 1, INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, ` kg`) - INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, `(`) - 1), `,`, ``) AS REAL)
  FROM `table_1_10006830_1`
  ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, `(`) + 1, INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, ` kg`) - INSTR(`Max Gross Weight`, `(`) - 1), `,`, ``) AS REAL) DESC
  LIMIT 1
) / (
  SELECT CAST(SUBSTR(`Max disk Loading`, INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, `(`) + 1, INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, ` kg/m²)`) - INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, `(`) - 1) AS REAL)
  FROM `table_1_10006830_1`
  ORDER BY CAST(SUBSTR(`Max disk Loading`, INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, `(`) + 1, INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, ` kg/m²)`) - INSTR(`Max disk Loading`, `(`) - 1) AS REAL) ASC
  LIMIT 1
) AS `Theoretical_Pterosaur_Wing_Area_m2`;
db_sql: SELECT (SELECT CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col2, INSTR(col2, '(') + 1, INSTR(col2, ' kg') - INSTR(col2, '(') - 1), ',', '') AS REAL) FROM `table_1_10006830_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col2, INSTR(col2, '(') + 1, INSTR(col2, ' kg') - INSTR(col2, '(') - 1), ',', '') AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1) / (SELECT CAST(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '(') + 1, INSTR(col4, ' kg/m²)') - INSTR(col4, '(') - 1) AS REAL) FROM `table_1_10006830_1` ORDER BY CAST(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '(') + 1, INSTR(col4, ' kg/m²)') - INSTR(col4, '(') - 1) AS REAL) ASC LIMIT 1) AS `Theoretical_Pterosaur_Wing_Area_m2`;
reasoning: The persona is setting up a hypothetical scenario for their flight model. They are using the heaviest helicopter as a proxy for the pterosaur's mass and the most 'efficient' (lowest) disk loading as a proxy for its lift system to calculate a theoretical wing area.
seeding_value: A biomechanist modeling the flight mechanics of giant pterosaurs by using heavy-lift helicopters as a modern mechanical analog. Goals: To create a realistic flight model for creatures like the Quetzalcoatlus, using the helicopter data to calculate the required wing area and power-to-weight ratios needed to lift an animal with a mass comparable to the heaviest aircraft in the table. Example Queries: Find the aircraft with the highest and lowest disk loading to understand the range of efficiency in powered lift. Assuming a pterosaur weighed as much as a CH-53E Super Stallion, what would its theoretical 'wing disk area' need to be if it operated at the more efficient disk loading of a light helicopter like the Bell 206B3? Correlate 'Max Gross Weight' with 'Total disk area' to establish a power law for scaling lift capacity, which can then be applied to biological models.

db_sql: SELECT col0, col3, col4 FROM `table_1_10015132_3` WHERE col3 NOT LIKE '%Center%' AND CAST(SUBSTR(col4, 1, 4) AS INTEGER) <= 1998 AND (CAST(CASE WHEN INSTR(col4, '-') > 0 THEN CASE WHEN LENGTH(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '-') + 1)) = 2 THEN '19' || SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '-') + 1) ELSE SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '-') + 1) END ELSE col4 END AS INTEGER) - CAST(SUBSTR(col4, 1, 4) AS INTEGER)) >= 4;
reasoning: This question frames the data request as a search for a historical comparison, a common task for researchers looking to create talking points for commentators.
seeding_value: A Broadcast Researcher for a major sports network. They are responsible for supplying on-air commentators with compelling statistics and historical context for live Toronto Raptors game broadcasts. Goals: To find interesting historical connections between players, generate data for on-screen graphics, and prepare talking points for the broadcast team about the franchise's history. Example Queries: Find all players who came from the same school as Vince Carter (North Carolina) to create a graphic about the 'UNC to Toronto' pipeline. nl: Show me the players whose timelines seem to have split. I need the ones who were titans in singles, winning more than twice what they lost, yet posted a losing record in doubles. And give me the inverse too—the doubles specialists who dominated with a partner but were lost when playing alone.
sql: SELECT `Player`, `Years Played`, `Singles W-L`, `Doubles W-L` FROM `table_1_10023387_1` WHERE (CAST(SUBSTR(`Singles W-L`, 1, INSTR(`Singles W-L`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) / CAST(SUBSTR(`Singles W-L`, INSTR(`Singles W-L`, '–') + 1) AS REAL) > 2 AND CAST(SUBSTR(`Doubles W-L`, 1, INSTR(`Doubles W-L`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) < CAST(SUBSTR(`Doubles W-L`, INSTR(`Doubles W-L`, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) OR (CAST(SUBSTR(`Doubles W-L`, 1, INSTR(`Doubles W-L`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) / CAST(SUBSTR(`Doubles W-L`, INSTR(`Doubles W-L`, '–') + 1) AS REAL) > 2 AND CAST(SUBSTR(`Singles W-L`, 1, INSTR(`Singles W-L`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) < CAST(SUBSTR(`Singles W-L`, INSTR(`Singles W-L`, '–') + 1) AS REAL));
db_sql: SELECT col0, col1, col3, col4 FROM `table_1_10023387_1` WHERE (CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) / CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL) > 2 AND CAST(SUBSTR(col4, 1, INSTR(col4, '–') - 1) AS REAL) < CAST(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) OR (CAST(SUBSTR(col4, 1, INSTR(col4, '–') - 1) AS REAL) / CAST(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '–') + 1) AS REAL) > 2 AND CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) < CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL));
reasoning: The author sees these players as living paradoxes, where their career path split into two wildly different outcomes. This stark contrast between singles and doubles performance is the perfect 'inciting incident' for a story about a choice that created two parallel timelines.
seeding_value: A speculative fiction author who crafts stories about temporal paradoxes, using the careers of athletes as a narrative device to explore alternate timelines. Goals: To identify players whose careers were unusually short or had starkly different outcomes in singles versus doubles, using these statistical anomalies as 'nexus points' for fictional stories where a single different choice could have created a legendary champion or a forgotten footnote. Example Queries: Find all players who played for only one year and had a winless record, representing potential timelines that were 'pruned' early. Identify players with a winning record in one discipline (e.g., Doubles W-L > 50%) but a losing record in the other (e.g., Singles W-L < 50%), to explore parallel selves who specialized differently. List players from the same era (e.g., 1988-1992) with wildly different career lengths and success rates, to brainstorm a story about two rivals whose paths diverged dramatically at a key tournament.

nl: Put the two vectors head-to-head for the critical years of '33, '34, and '35. Generate a table showing the raw case counts and the annual rate of change for the Typhus 'famine indicator' directly next to the same data for the Malaria 'ecological indicator'.
sql:
WITH LaggedData AS (
  SELECT
    `Year`,
    `Typhus`,
    CAST(REPLACE(`Malaria`, ' (avg)', '') AS REAL) AS `Malaria_Clean`,
    LAG(`Typhus`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `Year`) AS `Prev_Typhus`,
    LAG(CAST(REPLACE(`Malaria`, ' (avg)', '') AS REAL), 1) OVER (ORDER BY `Year`) AS `Prev_Malaria`
  FROM
    `table_1_1007688_1`
)
SELECT
  `Year`,
  `Typhus` AS `Typhus_Famine_Indicator`,
  ROUND(((`Typhus` - `Prev_Typhus`) * 100.0 / `Prev_Typhus`), 2) AS `Typhus_YoY_Change_%`,
  `Malaria_Clean` AS `Malaria_Ecological_Indicator`,
  ROUND(((`Malaria_Clean` - `Prev_Malaria`) * 100.0 / `Prev_Malaria`), 2) AS `Malaria_YoY_Change_%`
FROM
  LaggedData
WHERE
  CAST(SUBSTR(`Year`, 1, 4) AS INTEGER) IN (1933, 1934, 1935);
db_sql:
WITH LaggedData AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col1,
    CAST(REPLACE(col5, ' (avg)', '') AS REAL) AS `Malaria_Clean`,
    LAG(col1, 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `Prev_Typhus`,
    LAG(CAST(REPLACE(col5, ' (avg)', '') AS REAL), 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `Prev_Malaria`
  FROM
    `table_1_1007688_1`
)
SELECT
  col0,
  col1 AS `Typhus_Famine_Indicator`,
  ROUND(((col1 - `Prev_Typhus`) * 100.0 / `Prev_Typhus`), 2) AS `Typhus_YoY_Change_%`,
  `Malaria_Clean` AS `Malaria_Ecological_Indicator`,
  ROUND(((`Malaria_Clean` - `Prev_Malaria`) * 100.0 / `Prev_Malaria`), 2) AS `Malaria_YoY_Change_%`
FROM
  LaggedData
WHERE
  CAST(SUBSTR(col0, 1, 4) AS INTEGER) IN (1933, 1934, 1935);
reasoning: This question seeks a direct, side-by-side comparison to build a compelling narrative. The persona wants to juxtapose the two trends to argue that the ecological disaster (Malaria) followed a different, and perhaps more sinister, trajectory than the immediate humanitarian crisis (Typhus).
seeding_value: A paleo-parasitologist who posits that government-induced famines create unique ecological signatures, using historical disease data to track the rise and fall of insect vectors as bio-indicators of state-sponsored environmental collapse. Goals: To prove a controversial theory that the massive Malaria outbreak following the Holodomor was not merely a consequence of weakened immunity, but a direct result of agricultural collectivization creating vast, unmanaged wetlands, which served as ideal mosquito breeding grounds and constituted a second, ecological wave of the catastrophe. Example Queries: Compare the post-famine trajectory (1933-1935) of Malaria (a vector-borne illness) against Typhus (a louse-borne illness) to highlight Malaria's unique and delayed explosion. Calculate the ratio of Typhus to Malaria for the 1918-22 crisis versus the 1932-34 period to demonstrate that the ecological conditions of the Holodomor favored mosquito proliferation in a way the earlier crisis did not. Identify the year when the incidence of Typhus, the classic 'famine fever', began to decline, and then track the percentage growth of Malaria in the subsequent years to pinpoint the start of the 'ecological echo'.

It asks for the networks ('GROUP BY Network'), specifies the filter on viewership ('WHERE Viewers >= 4.0'), sets the condition on the group count ('HAVING COUNT > 1'), and requests both the network name and the final count ('SELECT Network, COUNT(...)').

nl: My hypothesis is that true culinary fusion happens where diasporic communities have a similar demographic weight. Where do we see the most balanced coexistence of significant Chinese, Japanese, and Korean populations? Let's filter for states where each group has at least 15,000 people and then sort them, starting with the most evenly distributed.
sql: SELECT `State/Territory`, `Japanese`, `Korean`, `Chinese`, (MIN(`Japanese`, `Korean`, `Chinese`) * 1.0 / MAX(`Japanese`, `Korean`, `Chinese`)) AS `balance_ratio` FROM `table_1_10118412_6` WHERE `Japanese` > 15000 AND `Korean` > 15000 AND `Chinese` > 15000 ORDER BY `balance_ratio` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col5, col6, col2, (MIN(col5, col6, col2) * 1.0 / MAX(col5, col6, col2)) AS `balance_ratio` FROM `table_1_10118412_6` WHERE col5 > 15000 AND col6 > 15000 AND col2 > 15000 ORDER BY `balance_ratio` DESC;
reasoning: This question uses the persona's academic jargon ('diasporic communities', 'demographic weight') to articulate their specific hypothesis. nl: Pinpoint the moment of maximum narrative velocity for me. I need to find the single greatest score improvement that happened after week 5, and tell me just how big that 'comeback intensity' was in raw points.
sql:
WITH ScoreChanges AS (
    SELECT
        `Week`,
        `Dance/song`,
        CAST(`Total` AS REAL) AS `CurrentScore`,
        LAG(CAST(`Total` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY CAST(`Week` AS REAL), ROWID) AS `PreviousScore`
    FROM
        `table_1_1014319_1`
    WHERE
        `Total` GLOB '[0-9]*[0-9]'
)
SELECT
    `Week` AS `Dip_Week`,
    (
        SELECT `Dance/song`
        FROM `table_1_1014319_1` AS t2
        WHERE CAST(t2.`Week` AS REAL) = sc.`Week` AND CAST(t2.`Total` AS REAL) = sc.`PreviousScore`
    ) AS `Dip_Dance`,
    sc.`PreviousScore` AS `Lowest_Score_After_Wk5`,
    sc.`CurrentScore` AS `Comeback_Score`,
    (sc.`CurrentScore` - sc.`PreviousScore`) AS `Comeback_Intensity`
FROM
    ScoreChanges sc
WHERE
    `Week` > 5 AND `PreviousScore` > 0
ORDER BY
    (`CurrentScore` - `PreviousScore`) DESC
LIMIT 1;
db_sql:
WITH ScoreChanges AS (
    SELECT
        col0,
        col1,
        CAST(col6 AS REAL) AS `CurrentScore`,
        LAG(CAST(col6 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY CAST(col0 AS REAL), ROWID) AS `PreviousScore`
    FROM
        `table_1_1014319_1`
    WHERE
        col6 GLOB '[0-9]*[0-9]'
)
SELECT
    col0 AS `Dip_Week`,
    (
        SELECT col1
        FROM `table_1_1014319_1` AS t2
        WHERE CAST(t2.col0 AS REAL) = sc.col0 AND CAST(t2.col6 AS REAL) = sc.`PreviousScore`
    ) AS `Dip_Dance`,
    sc.`PreviousScore` AS `Lowest_Score_After_Wk5`,
    sc.`CurrentScore` AS `Comeback_Score`,
    (sc.`CurrentScore` - sc.`PreviousScore`) AS `Comeback_Intensity`
FROM
    ScoreChanges sc
WHERE
    col0 > 5 AND `PreviousScore` > 0
ORDER BY
    (`CurrentScore` - `PreviousScore`) DESC
LIMIT 1;
reasoning: The persona is obsessed with 'narrative beats' and quantifies them with terms like 'intensity' or 'velocity'. They need to find the single most impactful moment of recovery to use as a model for future story arcs.

FROM
  `table_1_101942_2`

nl: For which seasons did George Utley score in the FA Cup and also play in more than 40 total games? Provide the season and total goals for those years, sorted from the fewest total goals to the most.
sql: WITH `CupScoringSeasons` AS (SELECT `Season`, `Total Goals`, `Total Apps` FROM `table_1_10240125_1` WHERE `FA Cup Goals` > `0`) SELECT `Season`, `Total Goals` FROM `CupScoringSeasons` WHERE `Total Apps` > `40` ORDER BY `Total Goals` ASC;
db_sql: WITH `CupScoringSeasons` AS (SELECT col0, col7, col6 FROM `table_1_10240125_1` WHERE col5 > 0) SELECT col0, col7 FROM `CupScoringSeasons` WHERE col6 > 40 ORDER BY col7 ASC;
reasoning:
1. Parse SQL Intent -> The query first identifies seasons with FA Cup goals greater than zero. From this subset, it selects seasons where total appearances are over 40. Finally, it retrieves the season and total goals for these filtered results, ordering them by total goals in ascending order.
2. Map to Schema -> `Season` maps to the 'Season' column, `Total Goals` to 'Total Goals', `FA Cup Goals` to 'FA Cup Goals', and `Total Apps` to 'Total Apps'. The conditions `> 0` and `> 40` are applied to the respective columns.
3. Draft Question -> "For which seasons did George Utley score in the FA Cup and also play in more than 40 total games? Provide the season and total goals for those years, sorted from the fewest total goals to the most."
4. Validate -> The question correctly specifies the two conditions (FA Cup goals and total appearances). It asks for the correct output (season, total goals) and includes the ascending order. It avoids technical jargon and is a natural phrasing.

nl: Let's create a comparative performance profile. For both the pre-war and post-war career segments, can you show me his average league goals, his FA Cup goals-per-game ratio, and the percentage of his total goals that were scored in the cup?
sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN `Season` IN ('1913–14', '1914–15')
    THEN 'Pre-War'
    ELSE 'Post-War'
  END AS `Career_Period`,
  AVG(`League Goals`) AS `Avg_League_Goals`,
  SUM(`FA Cup Goals`) * 1.0 / SUM(`FA Cup Apps`) AS `FA_Cup_Goals_Per_Game`,
  SUM(`FA Cup Goals`) * 1.0 / SUM(`Total Goals`) AS `FA_Cup_Share_of_Total_Goals`
FROM
  `table_1_10240125_2`
GROUP BY
  `Career_Period`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN col0 IN ('1913–14', '1914–15')
    THEN 'Pre-War'
    ELSE 'Post-War'
  END AS `Career_Period`,
  AVG(col3) AS `Avg_League_Goals`,
  SUM(col5) * 1.0 / SUM(col4) AS `FA_Cup_Goals_Per_Game`,
  SUM(col5) * 1.0 / SUM(col7) AS `FA_Cup_Share_of_Total_Goals`
FROM
  `table_1_10240125_2`
GROUP BY
  `Career_Period`;
reasoning: The persona needs a consolidated, data-driven profile to build their character's alternate history. This question bundles all the key metrics together to create a clear 'before and after' snapshot that forms the basis of their extrapolation.
seeding_value: A speculative historian writing an alternate-history novel where WWI was a brief, localized conflict, who uses football statistics as a socio-economic proxy to model what a 'lost generation' player's career might have become without the interruption. Goals: To extrapolate George Utley's pre-war performance trajectory to build a realistic, data-driven narrative for his character's uninterrupted career, focusing on whether his early FA Cup goal-scoring prowess would have translated into sustained league success. Example Queries: Calculate the ratio of FA Cup Goals to FA Cup Apps for the pre-war seasons (1913-15) to establish his 'big game' performance factor. Compare his average league appearances and goals per season before the four-year gap (1913-15) to his average after the gap (1919-22) to quantify the statistical decline. Was there a season where his total goals were significantly higher than his league goals, indicating a specialization in cup competitions?

db_sql: SELECT `t1`.col0, `t2`.col0, `t1`.col1 FROM `table_1_10262329_1` AS `t1` JOIN `table_1_10262329_1` AS `t2` ON `t1`.col1 = `t2`.col1 WHERE `t1`.col0 < `t2`.col0 AND (`t1`.col2 <> `t2`.col2 OR `t1`.col3 <> `t2`.col3);
reasoning: The SQL query performs a self-join to find pairs of 'Assembly Type'. The join condition requires these pairs to share the same 'Adhesive Type'. nl: We're not building a flash-in-the-pan program; we're building a dynasty. I need to see which schools have proven they can adapt and win as their communities have grown. Filter it down to just the schools with championships in different classes, then show me every class they've won and the initial year they secured that victory.
sql:
WITH `UnpivotedWinners` AS (
  SELECT `School Year`, `Class A` AS `School`, `Class A` AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `School Year`, `Class AA` AS `School`, `Class AA` AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `School Year`, `Class AAA` AS `School`, `Class AAA` AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `School Year`, `Class AAAA` AS `School`, `Class AAAA` AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `School Year`, `Class AAAAA` AS `School`, `Class AAAAA` AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
)
SELECT
  T1.`School`,
  T1.`Classification`,
  MIN(T1.`School Year`) AS `First_Year_Won_In_Class`
FROM `UnpivotedWinners` AS T1
WHERE
  T1.`School` IN (
    SELECT
      `School`
    FROM
      `UnpivotedWinners`
    GROUP BY
      `School`
    HAVING
      COUNT(DISTINCT `Classification`) > 1
  )
GROUP BY
  T1.`School`,
  T1.`Classification`
ORDER BY
  T1.`School`,
  `First_Year_Won_In_Class`;
db_sql:
WITH `UnpivotedWinners` AS (
  SELECT col0, col1 AS `School`, 'Class A' AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col2 AS `School`, 'Class AA' AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col3 AS `School`, 'Class AAA' AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col4 AS `School`, 'Class AAAA' AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col5 AS `School`, 'Class AAAAA' AS `Classification` FROM `table_1_10399701_2`
)
SELECT
  T1.`School`,
  T1.`Classification`,
  MIN(T1.col0) AS `First_Year_Won_In_Class`
FROM `UnpivotedWinners` AS T1
WHERE
  T1.`School` IN (
    SELECT
      `School`
    FROM
      `UnpivotedWinners`
    GROUP BY
      `School`
    HAVING
      COUNT(DISTINCT `Classification`) > 1
  )
GROUP BY
  T1.`School`,
  T1.`Classification`
ORDER BY
  T1.`School`,
  `First_Year_Won_In_Class`;

nl: List the names, orbital periods, and radial velocity measurements for all the exoplanets humanity detected using spectroscopic methods, will you?   `Radial velocity (m/s)`,
  `Detectable by:`
FROM table_1_10932739_2
WHERE
  `Detectable by:` LIKE '%spectrograph%'
ORDER BY
  CASE
    WHEN `Detectable by:` LIKE '%First-generation%'
    THEN 1
    WHEN `Detectable by:` LIKE '%Second-generation%'
    THEN 2
    WHEN `Detectable by:` LIKE '%Third-generation%'
    THEN 3
    ELSE 4
  END,
  CAST(REPLACE(`Radial velocity (m/s)`, ',', '') AS REAL);
db_sql:

  col0,
  col3,
  col4,
  col5
FROM table_1_10932739_2
WHERE
  col5 LIKE '%spectrograph%'
ORDER BY
  CASE
    WHEN col5 LIKE '%First-generation%'
    THEN 1
    WHEN col5 LIKE '%Second-generation%'
    THEN 2
    WHEN col5 LIKE '%Third-generation%'
    THEN 3
    ELSE 4
  END,
  CAST(REPLACE(col4, ',', '') AS REAL);

nl: What are the second and third fastest pairs of consecutive models in the performance ranking of Volvo 850s that are either turbocharged or use a Bosch Motronic 4.4 fuel delivery system?
sql:
WITH `RankedTurboPerformance` AS (
  SELECT
    `Trim`,
    CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Performance`, INSTR(`Performance`, ': ') + 2), 's', '') AS REAL) AS `AccelerationTime`,
    LAG(`Trim`, 1, `Top Model`) OVER (ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Performance`, INSTR(`Performance`, ': ') + 2), 's', '') AS REAL) DESC) AS `NextSlowerModel`
  FROM
    `table_1_11167610_1`
  WHERE
    `Performance` LIKE `'%0–100km/h:%'` AND (`Turbo` IS NOT `No` OR `Fuel Delivery` IS `Bosch Motronic 4.4`)
)
SELECT
  `NextSlowerModel`,
  `Trim` AS `FasterModel`
FROM
  `RankedTurboPerformance`
WHERE
  `NextSlowerModel` IS NOT `Top Model`
ORDER BY
  `AccelerationTime` ASC
LIMIT 2 OFFSET 1;
db_sql:
WITH `RankedTurboPerformance` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col7, INSTR(col7, ': ') + 2), 's', '') AS REAL) AS `AccelerationTime`,
    LAG(col0, 1, 'Top Model') OVER (ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col7, INSTR(col7, ': ') + 2), 's', '') AS REAL) DESC) AS `NextSlowerModel`
  FROM
    `table_1_11167610_1`
  WHERE
    col7 LIKE '%0–100km/h:%' AND (col2 IS NOT 'No' OR col3 IS 'Bosch Motronic 4.4')
)
SELECT
  `NextSlowerModel`,
  col0 AS `FasterModel`
FROM
  `RankedTurboPerformance`
WHERE
  `NextSlowerModel` IS NOT 'Top Model' AND 1 BETWEEN 0 AND 2
ORDER BY
  `AccelerationTime` ASC
LIMIT 2 OFFSET 1;
db_result: [('2.0 t-5 (some eu countries only)', '850 r (auto)'), ('2.4t', '2.0 t-5 (some eu countries only)')]
reasoning: This question focuses on the concept of "consecutive models" in a performance hierarchy, which is the relationship established by the `LAG` window function. It accurately specifies the group of models to consider and asks for specific "pairs" from the ranking. Requesting the "second and third fastest pairs" is a concise and natural way to express the combination of ordering by speed, offsetting by one, and limiting to two.

nl: Considering only the Super Aces hands that are not a 'four of a kind' and offer a greater payout jump between the 4th and 5th credit than between the 3rd and 4th, which is the most valuable hand based on its 1-credit payout, provided its payout is also above the average of all such qualifying hands?
sql:
WITH `BonusPayouts` AS (
  SELECT
    `Hand`,
    `1 credit`,
    `3 credits`,
    `4 credits`,
    CASE
      WHEN `Hand` = `Royal flush`
      THEN 4000
      ELSE CAST(`5 credits` AS REAL)
    END AS `FiveCreditValue`
  FROM `table_1_11200856_1`
  WHERE
    (`FiveCreditValue` - `4 credits`) > (`4 credits` - `3 credits`)
    AND `Hand` NOT LIKE `Four%kind`
)
SELECT
  `Hand`
FROM `BonusPayouts`
WHERE
  `1 credit` > (
    SELECT
      AVG(`1 credit`)
    FROM `BonusPayouts`
  )
GROUP BY
  `Hand`
ORDER BY
  `1 credit` DESC
LIMIT 1;
db_sql:
WITH `BonusPayouts` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col1
  FROM `table_1_11200856_1`
  WHERE
    (CAST(REPLACE(col5, '*', '') AS REAL) - col4) > (col4 - col3)
    AND col0 NOT LIKE 'Four%kind'
)
SELECT DISTINCT
  col0
FROM `BonusPayouts`
WHERE
  col1 > (
    SELECT
      AVG(col1)
    FROM `BonusPayouts`
  )
GROUP BY
  col0
ORDER BY
  col1 DESC
LIMIT 1;
reasoning: This question is framed as a single, complex sentence that emphasizes the final result while embedding the conditions. It uses more abstract terms like 'qualifying hands' to refer to the intermediate result set from the CTE. The goal is to find the 'most valuable hand based on its 1-credit payout,' which directly translates the `ORDER BY '1 credit' DESC LIMIT 1` logic, while the 'provided' and 'considering only' clauses cover the filtering conditions from the WHERE clauses.

nl: For the central case-study chapter of 'The Echo in the Stands,' I need a complete spatial profile for each team. Please generate a table showing the team, stadium, average empty seats, average and peak occupancy rates, and the attendance flux, arranging the data to spotlight the most cavernous fan experiences first.
sql:
SELECT
  `Team`,
  `Stadium`,
  (`Capacity` - `Average`) AS `Average_Empty_Seats`,
  CAST(`Average` AS REAL) / `Capacity` AS `Average_Occupancy_Rate`,
  CAST(`Highest` AS REAL) / `Capacity` AS `Peak_Occupancy_Rate`,
  (`Highest` - `Lowest`) AS `Attendance_Flux`
FROM
  `table_1_11206787_5`
ORDER BY
  `Average_Occupancy_Rate` ASC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col0,
  col1,
  (col2 - col5) AS `Average_Empty_Seats`,
  CAST(col5 AS REAL) / col2 AS `Average_Occupancy_Rate`,
  CAST(col3 AS REAL) / col2 AS `Peak_Occupancy_Rate`,
  (col3 - col4) AS `Attendance_Flux`
FROM
  `table_1_11206787_5`
ORDER BY
  `Average_Occupancy_Rate` ASC;
reasoning: This is a comprehensive request that synthesizes all the calculated fields from the SQL query. It frames the data need in the context of the persona's final output—a monograph—and uses their specific terminology ('spatial profile,' 'cavernous') to ask for the complete dataset in one go.

Goals: To write a monograph titled 'The Echo in the Stands,' using the 2007-08 Scottish Second Division as a case study to argue that oversized, under-filled stadiums (like Queen's Park at Hampden) create a distinct form of community identity rooted in shared emptiness rather than collective noise. Example Queries: Calculate an 'Emptiness Ratio' for each stadium by comparing average attendance to total capacity, identifying which team plays in the vastest space relative to its crowd. Which team has the biggest swing between its highest and lowest attendance, suggesting a fanbase motivated by specific events rather than routine support? On each team's best day (highest attendance), what percentage of their stadium was still empty? Rank them to see who had the most unfilled seats even at their peak.

nl: For the years when more than 2000 Jamaicans were granted British citizenship, what was the combined total of naturalizations by residence and marriage, and which of those two pathways was more dominant? Please show the years with the highest combined totals first.
sql:
SELECT
  `Year`,
  `Naturalisation by residence` + `Naturalisation by marriage` AS `Main_Pathways_Total`,
  CASE
    WHEN CAST(`Naturalisation by residence` AS REAL) > `Naturalisation by marriage`
    THEN `Residence was dominant`
    ELSE `Marriage was dominant or equal`
  END AS `Dominant_Pathway_Comparison`
FROM
  `table_1_11214212_1`
WHERE
  `Numer of Jamaicans granted British citizenship` > `2000`
ORDER BY
  `Main_Pathways_Total` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col2 + col3 AS `Main_Pathways_Total`, CASE WHEN col2 > col3 THEN 'Residence was dominant' ELSE 'Marriage was dominant or equal' END AS `Dominant_Pathway_Comparison` FROM `table_1_11214212_1` WHERE col1 > 2000 ORDER BY `Main_Pathways_Total` DESC;

reasoning: This question is a direct and comprehensive translation of the query's logic. It explicitly asks for each component: the filter (total citizenship > 2000), the calculation (sum of two columns), the comparison (residence vs. marriage), and the sorting order (descending by the sum). It breaks down the request into clear, sequential parts, mirroring the SQL structure.

nl: Okay, let's generate the final dataset for my paper. Please provide a list of every Grand Final at Stadium Australia where the underdog—defined by fewer prior appearances—was victorious, sorted primarily by the narrowest point margin and secondarily by the highest attendance. This will give us the clearest view of the emotional resonance in action.
sql: WITH `TeamAppearances` AS (SELECT CASE WHEN INSTR(`Team`, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(`Team`, 1, INSTR(`Team`, ' (') - 1) ELSE `Team` END AS `BaseTeam`, COUNT(*) AS `TotalAppearances` FROM (SELECT `WinningTeam` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_11236195_5` UNION ALL SELECT `LosingTeam` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_11236195_5`) GROUP BY `BaseTeam`) SELECT T1.`Season`, T1.`WinningTeam`, T1.`LosingTeam`, T1.`GF Attendance`, CAST(SUBSTR(T1.`Score`, 1, INSTR(T1.`Score`, '-') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(T1.`Score`, INSTR(T1.`Score`, '-') + 1) AS REAL) AS `PointMargin`, WA.`TotalAppearances` AS `WinnerAppearances`, LA.`TotalAppearances` AS `LoserAppearances` FROM `table_1_11236195_5` AS T1 JOIN `TeamAppearances` AS WA ON (CASE WHEN INSTR(T1.`WinningTeam`, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(T1.`WinningTeam`, 1, INSTR(T1.`WinningTeam`, ' (') - 1) ELSE T1.`WinningTeam` END) = WA.`BaseTeam` JOIN `TeamAppearances` AS LA ON (CASE WHEN INSTR(T1.`LosingTeam`, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(T1.`LosingTeam`, 1, INSTR(T1.`LosingTeam`, ' (') - 1) ELSE T1.`LosingTeam` END) = LA.`BaseTeam` WHERE T1.`Location` LIKE '%Stadium Australia%' AND WA.`TotalAppearances` < LA.`TotalAppearances` ORDER BY `PointMargin` ASC, T1.`GF Attendance` DESC;
db_sql: WITH `TeamAppearances` AS (SELECT CASE WHEN INSTR(`Team`, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(`Team`, 1, INSTR(`Team`, ' (') - 1) ELSE `Team` END AS `BaseTeam`, COUNT(*) AS `TotalAppearances` FROM (SELECT col2 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_11236195_5` UNION ALL SELECT col4 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_11236195_5`) GROUP BY `BaseTeam`) SELECT T1.col0, T1.col2, T1.col4, T1.col6, CAST(SUBSTR(T1.col3, 1, INSTR(T1.col3, '-') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(T1.col3, INSTR(T1.col3, '-') + 1) AS REAL) AS `PointMargin`, WA.`TotalAppearances` AS `WinnerAppearances`, LA.`TotalAppearances` AS `LoserAppearances` FROM `table_1_11236195_5` AS T1 JOIN `TeamAppearances` AS WA ON (CASE WHEN INSTR(T1.col2, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(T1.col2, 1, INSTR(T1.col2, ' (') - 1) ELSE T1.col2 END) = WA.`BaseTeam` JOIN `TeamAppearances` AS LA ON (CASE WHEN INSTR(T1.col4, ' (') > 0 THEN SUBSTR(T1.col4, 1, INSTR(T1.col4, ' (') - 1) ELSE T1.col4 END) = LA.`BaseTeam` WHERE T1.col5 LIKE '%Stadium Australia%' AND WA.`TotalAppearances` < LA.`TotalAppearances` ORDER BY `PointMargin` ASC, T1.col6 DESC;

nl: I'm interested in engine models that use 80/87 octane fuel. Can you find any compression ratios that are used by three or more of these models and list the names of the engines for me?
sql:
SELECT
  GROUP_CONCAT(`Engine`) AS `Grouped_Engines`,
  `Compression ratio`
FROM
  `table_1_1123802_1`
WHERE
  `Octane rating` = `80/87`
GROUP BY
  `Compression ratio`
HAVING
  COUNT(`Engine`) > 2
ORDER BY
  `Supercharger gear ratio` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  GROUP_CONCAT(col0),
  col4
FROM
  `table_1_1123802_1`
WHERE
  col6 = '80/87'
GROUP BY
  col4
HAVING
  COUNT(col0) > 2
ORDER BY
  col5 DESC;

nl: I need to see a list of characters and their immediate successors. To create this list, first separate characters into three timelines: one for those connected to Taylor, one for Flack, and one for the rest. Order each timeline by first appearance. Then, give me the top five pairs of characters from these timelines, ordered from the most recent to the oldest based on when the first character of the pair appeared.
sql: WITH `RankedAppearances` AS (SELECT `Character`, `Relationship`, `First appearance`, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY (CASE WHEN `Relationship` LIKE `%Taylor%` THEN 1 WHEN `Relationship` LIKE `%Flack%` THEN 2 ELSE 3 END) ORDER BY `First appearance` ASC) AS `Rank` FROM `table_1_11240028_3`) SELECT T1.`Character` AS `Preceding Character`, T2.`Character` AS `Succeeding Character` FROM `RankedAppearances` AS T1 LEFT OUTER JOIN `RankedAppearances` AS T2 ON T1.`Rank` + 1 = T2.`Rank` WHERE T1.`Character` IS NOT T2.`Character` AND EXISTS (SELECT * FROM `table_1_11240028_3` AS T3 WHERE T3.`Character` IS NOT NULL OR T3.`Relationship` ISNULL) GROUP BY `Preceding Character`, `Succeeding Character` HAVING T1.`Character` IS NOT NULL AND T2.`Character` IS NOT NULL ORDER BY T1.`First appearance` DESC, T2.`First appearance` ASC LIMIT 5 OFFSET 0;
db_sql: WITH `RankedAppearances` AS (SELECT col0, col3, CASE WHEN col2 LIKE '%Taylor%' THEN 1 WHEN col2 LIKE '%Flack%' THEN 2 ELSE 3 END AS `part`, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY CASE WHEN col2 LIKE '%Taylor%' THEN 1 WHEN col2 LIKE '%Flack%' THEN 2 ELSE 3 END ORDER BY col3 ASC) AS `rnk` FROM `table_1_11240028_3`) SELECT T1.col0 AS `Preceding Character`, T2.col0 AS `Succeeding Character` FROM `RankedAppearances` AS T1 INNER JOIN `RankedAppearances` AS T2 ON T1.`part` = T2.`part` AND T1.`rnk` + 1 = T2.`rnk` WHERE TRUE GROUP BY T1.col0, T2.col0, T1.col3, T2.col3 ORDER BY T1.col3 DESC, T2.col3 ASC LIMIT 5 OFFSET 0;
db_result: [('terrence davis', 'samantha flack'), ('ellie danville', 'russ josephson'), ('reed garrett', 'claire conrad taylor'), ('rikki sandoval', 'ellie danville')]
reasoning: The query's logic can be described as creating separate timelines for different character relationship groups. Within each timeline (Taylor, Flack, other), characters are ordered by their first appearance. The query then finds who immediately followed whom on each timeline and presents the top five such pairings, prioritizing pairs that start with a more recently introduced character.

nl: Find the prophetic moments for 'Big Shots' where the show's fate was sealed. Show me the episodes, their titles, and air dates where the audience's departure—the viewer drop—numerically mirrored the episode's own identifier.
sql:
WITH `EpisodeVibrations` AS (
  SELECT
    `#`,
    `Episode`,
    `Air Date`,
    (
      LAG(CAST(`Viewers (m)` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY `#`) - CAST(`Viewers (m)` AS REAL)
    ) AS `Viewer_Drop`
  FROM
    `table_1_11244302_1`
)
SELECT
  `#` AS `Episode_Resonance_Number`,
  `Episode` AS `Title_of_Omen`,
  `Air Date` AS `Date_of_Echo`,
  `Viewer_Drop`
FROM
  `EpisodeVibrations`
WHERE
  `Viewer_Drop` > 0
  AND REPLACE(printf('%.2f', `Viewer_Drop`), '.', '') LIKE '%' || CAST(`#` AS TEXT) || '%'
ORDER BY
  `#`;
db_sql:
WITH `EpisodeVibrations` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col1,
    col2,
    (
      LAG(CAST(col7 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY col0) - CAST(col7 AS REAL)
    ) AS `Viewer_Drop`
  FROM
    `table_1_11244302_1`
)
SELECT
  col0 AS `Episode_Resonance_Number`,
  col1 AS `Title_of_Omen`,
  col2 AS `Date_of_Echo`,
  `Viewer_Drop`
FROM
  `EpisodeVibrations`
WHERE
  `Viewer_Drop` > 0
  AND REPLACE(printf('%.2f', `Viewer_Drop`), '.', '') LIKE '%' || CAST(CAST(col0 AS INTEGER) AS TEXT) || '%'
ORDER BY
  col0;

Goals: To develop and back-test a predictive model called the 'Audience Decay Algorithm,' which uses the rate of viewer loss and the 'vibrational frequency' of episode numbers to predict a show's cancellation date with mystical accuracy. Example Queries: Calculate the week-over-week percentage decline in 'Viewers (m)' to find the show's 'Decay Velocity' and see if it accelerates after a prime number episode (#2, #3, #5, #7). Was the drop in ratings between the pilot (Episode 1) and the finale (Episode 10) a perfect integer multiple of any of the numbers in the 18-49 share data? nl: Pinpoint the four most significant disturbances in the metaphysical flux. For each event, list its key, its date, the prior week's energy baseline, the current reading, and the final flux magnitude.
sql: WITH MetaphysicalFlux AS (SELECT `Episode`, `Air Date`, CAST(`Viewers (m)` AS REAL) AS `Viewers`, LAG(CAST(`Viewers (m)` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY `No.`) AS `PreviousViewers` FROM `table_1_11274401_3`) SELECT `Episode` AS `Event_Key`, `Air Date` AS `Event_Date`, `PreviousViewers`, `Viewers` AS `CurrentViewers`, (`Viewers` - `PreviousViewers`) AS `Flux_Magnitude` FROM MetaphysicalFlux WHERE `PreviousViewers` > 0 ORDER BY ABS(`Flux_Magnitude`) DESC LIMIT 4;
db_sql: WITH MetaphysicalFlux AS (SELECT col1, col2, CAST(col7 AS REAL) AS `Viewers`, LAG(CAST(col7 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `PreviousViewers` FROM `table_1_11274401_3`) SELECT col1 AS `Event_Key`, col2 AS `Event_Date`, `PreviousViewers`, `Viewers` AS `CurrentViewers`, (`Viewers` - `PreviousViewers`) AS `Flux_Magnitude` FROM MetaphysicalFlux WHERE `PreviousViewers` > 0 ORDER BY ABS(`Flux_Magnitude`) DESC LIMIT 4;

nl: Can you generate a summary report grouping the keepers by nationality? For each nation, I need to see the total number of players on the list, their average career span, and the proportion of their dismissals that were stumpings.
sql: SELECT `Nationality`, COUNT(*) AS `player_count`, AVG(CAST(SUBSTR(`Career Span`, 6, 4) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(`Career Span`, 1, 4) AS REAL) + 1) AS `avg_career_length`, CAST(SUM(`Stumpings`) AS REAL) * 100 / SUM(`Dismissals`) AS `stumping_percentage` FROM `table_1_11303072_9` WHERE `Career Span` NOT LIKE '%–' GROUP BY `Nationality` ORDER BY `player_count` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col3, COUNT(*) AS `player_count`, AVG(CAST(SUBSTR(col6, 6, 4) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(col6, 1, 4) AS REAL) + 1) AS `avg_career_length`, CAST(SUM(col5) AS REAL) * 100 / SUM(col1) AS `stumping_percentage` FROM `table_1_11303072_9` WHERE col6 NOT LIKE '%–' GROUP BY col3 ORDER BY `player_count` DESC;
reasoning: This is a comprehensive request that a statistician would make to an analyst, combining all the required metrics into a single, report-ready format. It covers all components of the SQL query: the grouping, the three calculated metrics, and the sorting order.
seeding_value: A Cricket Statistician working for a national cricket board, tasked with compiling historical performance data for coaching and player development programs. They are currently analyzing the traits and career arcs of the world's most successful wicket-keepers to identify benchmarks for aspiring players. Goals: To identify national trends among elite wicket-keepers, analyze the balance between different dismissal types (catches vs. stumpings), and understand the typical career duration of top-tier players. Example Queries: What is the distribution of players by nationality in the top 10 list? Who has the highest ratio of stumpings to total dismissals? Calculate the career length for each player and show the average number of dismissals per year.

nl: I need to chart the full cycle of victory. Show me each year's Open 1st VIII champion, and then tell me what their 'Foundational Chi Level' was—that is, the total number of U15 race wins they secured—exactly three years before their ultimate manifestation of success.
sql:
WITH `U15_Energy_Focus` AS (
  SELECT `Crew` AS `year`, `school`, COUNT(*) AS `wins`
  FROM (
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 1st IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 2nd IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 3rd IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 4th IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 5th IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Crew`, `U15 6th IV` AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
  )
  GROUP BY `year`, `school`
)
SELECT
  T1.`Crew` AS `Manifestation_Year`,
  T1.`Open 1st VIII` AS `Champion_School`,
  COALESCE(T2.`wins`, 0) AS `Foundational_Chi_Level_3_Years_Prior`
FROM `table_1_11318462_5` AS T1
LEFT JOIN `U15_Energy_Focus` AS T2
  ON T1.`Crew` = T2.`year` + 3 AND T1.`Open 1st VIII` = T2.`school`
ORDER BY
  T1.`Crew`;
db_sql:
WITH `U15_Energy_Focus` AS (
  SELECT col0 AS `year`, `school`, COUNT(*) AS `wins`
  FROM (
    SELECT col0, col7 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, col8 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, col9 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, col10 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, col11 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, col12 AS `school` FROM `table_1_11318462_5`
  )
  GROUP BY `year`, `school`
)
SELECT
  T1.col0 AS `Manifestation_Year`,
  T1.col1 AS `Champion_School`,
  COALESCE(T2.`wins`, 0) AS `Foundational_Chi_Level_3_Years_Prior`
FROM `table_1_11318462_5` AS T1
LEFT JOIN `U15_Energy_Focus` AS T2
  ON T1.col0 = T2.`year` + 3 AND T1.col1 = T2.`school`
ORDER BY
  T1.col0;
reasoning: The persona views a future championship win as a 'manifestation' of energy cultivated years earlier. This question frames the data request as a way to measure the strength of that initial energy source.
seeding_value: An institutional geomancer who believes patterns of victory in school competitions are dictated by the 'competitive Feng Shui' of a campus and its boathouse, not just talent. Goals: To create a 'prospectus of success' using this historical data to prove their theories, hoping to be hired by an underperforming school to realign their 'winning energy' by recommending changes to their facilities, symbols, or even race-day rituals. Example Queries: Identify 'dynastic flows' by finding which school (e.g., BGS) won the same event for the most consecutive years, suggesting a powerfully aligned energy source. Track the 'progression of chi' by checking if the winners of the senior 'Open 1st VIII' event had also won any U15 events three years prior, indicating that success energy matures with the cohort. Pinpoint years of 'energetic disruption', such as 2000, to see if one school's sudden dominance (TSS) across many categories correlated with a major campus renovation or a change in their school crest.

nl: Show me the opponent, date, and match status (victory or defeat) for every game Ana Timotić played after the 2005 edition.

  `Opponent`,
  `Date`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Outcome` = `Win`
    THEN `VICTORY`
    ELSE `DEFEAT`
  END AS `match_status`
FROM
  `table_1_11326124_3`
WHERE
  `Edition` > `2005`;

nl: For every team that has won Group C, can you tell me if they have also ever won Group D? Please list the teams alphabetically.
sql:
SELECT DISTINCT
  T1.`Group C Winner` AS `Team`,
  CASE
    WHEN EXISTS (
      SELECT
        1
      FROM
        `table_1_1137142_1`
      WHERE
        `Group D Winner` = T1.`Group C Winner`
    )
    THEN `Also Won Group D`
    ELSE `Never Won Group D`
  END AS `Status`
FROM
  `table_1_1137142_1` AS T1
ORDER BY
  `Team` ASC;
db_sql: SELECT DISTINCT T1.col3 AS `Team`, CASE WHEN EXISTS ( SELECT 1 FROM `table_1_1137142_1` WHERE col4 = T1.col3 ) THEN 'Also Won Group D' ELSE 'Never Won Group D' END AS `Status` FROM `table_1_1137142_1` AS T1 ORDER BY `Team` ASC;
db_result: [('brindisi', 'Never Won Group D'), ('casertana', 'Never Won Group D'), ('fano', 'Never Won Group D'), ('fidelis andria', 'Never Won Group D'), ('francavilla', 'Never Won Group D'), ('giulianova', 'Never Won Group D'), ('jesi', 'Never Won Group D'), ('perugia', 'Never Won Group D'), ('siena', 'Never Won Group D'), ('teramo', 'Never Won Group D'), ('vis pesaro', 'Never Won Group D')]
reasoning:
1. Parse SQL Intent: The query first identifies all unique teams that have won 'Group C'. Then, for each of these teams, it checks if that team's name also appears in the 'Group D Winner' column. Finally, it labels each team based on this check and sorts the results alphabetically by team name.
2. Map to Schema: This involves selecting distinct values from the 'Group C Winner' column. The core logic is a conditional check (CASE WHEN EXISTS) that compares each 'Group C Winner' against all values in the 'Group D Winner' column.
3. Draft Question: "For every team that has won Group C, can you tell me if they have also ever won Group D? Please list the teams alphabetically."
4. Validate: This question accurately captures the intent. It specifies the primary group (Group C), the condition to check against (winning Group D), and the desired sorting, all without using any technical jargon.

nl: For the Symbian case file, I need to prepare two key exhibits. Exhibit A is 'Corporate Push,' based on units sold and shipped. Exhibit B is 'Active User Base,' based on browsing. Calculate the average market share for both exhibits.
sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN `Method` IN (`units sold`, `units shipped`) THEN `Corporate_Sales_Focus`
    WHEN `Method` = `browsing` THEN `Actual_User_Activity`
  END AS `Evidence_Type`,
  AVG(CAST(REPLACE(`Symbian / Series 40`, `%`, ``) AS REAL)) AS `Average_Market_Share`
FROM `table_1_11381701_3`
WHERE
  `Symbian / Series 40` IS NOT `N/A` AND `Method` IN (`units sold`, `units shipped`, `browsing`)
GROUP BY
  `Evidence_Type`
ORDER BY
  `Average_Market_Share` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN col2 IN ('units sold', 'units shipped') THEN 'Corporate_Sales_Focus'
    WHEN col2 = 'browsing' THEN 'Actual_User_Activity'
  END AS `Evidence_Type`,
  AVG(CAST(REPLACE(col6, '%', '') AS REAL)) AS `Average_Market_Share`
FROM `table_1_11381701_3`
WHERE
  col6 != 'N/A' AND col2 IN ('units sold', 'units shipped', 'browsing')
GROUP BY
  `Evidence_Type`
ORDER BY
  `Average_Market_Share` DESC;
reasoning: This question adopts the legalistic tone of the persona, referring to the data as 'evidence' and the categories as 'exhibits.' This directly translates the SQL's `CASE` statement into the language of someone building a legal case file.
seeding_value: A forensic nostalgia analyst who investigates historical data to pinpoint the 'moment of betrayal' when tech companies abandoned promising platforms, leaving loyal user bases stranded. Goals: To build a legal and emotional case file for a class-action lawsuit on behalf of former BlackBerry and Symbian users, arguing that the companies misrepresented the long-term viability of their ecosystems, using the discrepancy between 'units sold' and 'active browsing' as evidence of a large, abandoned user community. Example Queries: Find the greatest discrepancy between a platform's 'units sold' share and its 'browsing' share to identify the most abandoned, yet still active, user base. Which source (Gartner, IDC, etc.) showed the steepest decline for BlackBerry between May and August 2013, representing the peak of the platform's collapse? Aggregate the total market share for all non-iOS/Android platforms to quantify the size of the 'alternative ecosystem' that was ultimately dismantled.

nl: Map the temporal divergences from the 1988 season. I need to see every Grand Prix where the dominant Prost-Senna timeline fractured, specifically in pole position and fastest lap. Pinpoint the event, identify the apparition responsible, and classify the nature of the ripple.

nl: For countries with over 5 total victories, if female runners have secured more wins than male runners, what is the total number of wins by women? Please list these countries starting with the one with the most overall wins.
sql: SELECT `Country`, CASE WHEN (`Marathon (womens)` + `Half Marathon (womens)`) > (`Marathon (mens)` + `Half Marathon (mens)`) THEN (`Marathon (womens)` + `Half Marathon (womens)`) END AS `Female_Led_Wins` FROM `table_1_11391954_3` WHERE `Total` > 5 ORDER BY `Total` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, CASE WHEN (col3 + col5) > (col2 + col4) THEN (col3 + col5) END AS `Female_Led_Wins` FROM `table_1_11391954_3` WHERE col1 > 5 ORDER BY col1 DESC;
reasoning: The SQL query filters for countries with more than 5 total wins (`WHERE Total > 5`). It then calculates total female wins and total male wins, displaying the female total only if it's greater (`CASE WHEN ...`). Finally, it sorts the results by the total number of wins in descending order. This question directly translates these steps into a formal, multi-part request.

nl: Which drivers demonstrated a clear chronodynamic resonance, converting the peak velocity of a fastest lap into a win at the subsequent temporal junction? I require a list of these drivers, the races where this resonance culminated, and the corresponding dates.
sql:
WITH `LaggedPerformances` AS (
  SELECT
    `Rnd`,
    `Race`,
    `Date`,
    `Race Winner`,
    LAG(`Fastest Lap`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `Rnd`) AS `Previous_Fastest_Lap_Driver`
  FROM
    `table_1_1140076_2`
)
SELECT
  `Race Winner` AS `Driver_With_Momentum`,
  `Race` AS `Winning_Race`,
  `Date` AS `Date_Of_Win`
FROM
  `LaggedPerformances`
WHERE
  `Race Winner` = `Previous_Fastest_Lap_Driver`;
db_sql:
WITH `LaggedPerformances` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col1,
    col2,
    col6,
    LAG(col5, 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `Previous_Fastest_Lap_Driver`
  FROM
    `table_1_1140076_2`
)
SELECT
  col6 AS `Driver_With_Momentum`,
  col1 AS `Winning_Race`,
  col2 AS `Date_Of_Win`
FROM
  `LaggedPerformances`
WHERE
  col6 = `Previous_Fastest_Lap_Driver`;

reasoning: This query helps the persona identify moments of 'chronodynamic resonance,' where a driver's performance peak carries over a temporal gap between races. This is core evidence for their theory that performance is tied to time itself.

Goals: To develop a 'chronodynamic model' of motorsport by identifying patterns in the race calendar, believing that certain drivers or constructors resonate with specific times of the year, causing predictable surges or dips in performance independent of engineering. Example Queries: Which constructor had the shortest time gap between consecutive wins and where did those wins occur? sql: SELECT `Winning driver`, COUNT(*) AS `Total_Wins`, SUM(CASE WHEN `Constructor` = `Maserati` THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS `Maserati_Wins` FROM `table_1_1140111_5` GROUP BY `Winning driver` HAVING COUNT(*) > 1 ORDER BY `Total_Wins` DESC, `Maserati_Wins` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col3, COUNT(*) `Total_Wins`, SUM(CASE WHEN col4 = 'Maserati' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS `Maserati_Wins` FROM `table_1_1140111_5` GROUP BY col3 HAVING COUNT(*) > 1 ORDER BY `Total_Wins` DESC, `Maserati_Wins` DESC;
reasoning:
1. Parse SQL Intent -> The user wants to see winning drivers, their total win count, and their win count specifically with Maserati. The results are filtered to only include drivers with more than one win and are ordered by total wins, then Maserati wins, both descending.
2. Map to Schema -> Map `Winning driver` to 'winning driver', `COUNT(*)` to 'total win count', `SUM(CASE WHEN Constructor = 'Maserati' ...)` to 'wins with Maserati', `HAVING COUNT(*) > 1` to 'won more than one race', and `ORDER BY` to 'sort the list'.
3. Draft Question -> "For drivers who won more than one non-championship race in 1957, list them along with their total win count and how many of those wins were with Maserati. Sort the list by the most total wins, and then by the most Maserati wins."

nl: For each director who has directed more than one episode, classify their average U.S. viewership as either above or below the overall series average, and list them in descending order of their average viewership.
sql:
WITH `DirectorStats` AS (
  SELECT
    `Director`,
    AVG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (millions)` AS REAL)) AS `AverageViewers`
  FROM `table_1_11404452_1`
  GROUP BY
    `Director`
  HAVING
    COUNT(`Series #`) > 1
), `Overall` AS (
  SELECT
    AVG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (millions)` AS REAL)) AS `GlobalAverage`
  FROM `table_1_11404452_1`
)
SELECT
  `DirectorStats`.`Director`,
  CASE
    WHEN `DirectorStats`.`AverageViewers` > `Overall`.`GlobalAverage` THEN `Above Average`
    ELSE `Below Average`
  END
FROM `DirectorStats`, `Overall`
ORDER BY
  `DirectorStats`.`AverageViewers` DESC;
db_sql: WITH `DirectorStats` AS (SELECT col3, AVG(CAST(col4 AS REAL)) AS `AverageViewers` FROM `table_1_11404452_1` GROUP BY col3 HAVING COUNT(col0) > 1), `Overall` AS (SELECT AVG(CAST(col4 AS REAL)) AS `GlobalAverage` FROM `table_1_11404452_1`) SELECT `DirectorStats`.col3, CASE WHEN `DirectorStats`.`AverageViewers` > `Overall`.`GlobalAverage` THEN 'Above Average' ELSE 'Below Average' END AS `Performance` FROM `DirectorStats`, `Overall` ORDER BY `DirectorStats`.`AverageViewers` DESC;
db_result: [('james hayman', 'Above Average'), ('lev l. spiro', 'Below Average'), ('tricia brock', 'Below Average')]
reasoning: This question directly mirrors the query's logic. It specifies the filter for directors with more than one episode ('directed more than one'), the comparison of averages ('above or below the overall series average'), and the final sorting criterion ('in descending order of their average viewership'). The language is formal and precise.

nl: To establish a baseline for my Host-Induced Outcome Dynamics theory, I need to see the distribution of 'podium potential' for each host. Show me the counts and percentages for first, second, and third place slots, partitioned by Carlos Lozano and Jesús Vázquez.
sql:
WITH `HostPlacementAnalysis` AS (
  SELECT `Host`, '1st Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Host`, '2nd Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Host`, '3rd Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
)
SELECT
  `Host`,
  `Placement`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Placement_Count`,
  ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / SUM(COUNT(*)) OVER (PARTITION BY `Host`), 2) AS `Distribution_Percentage`
FROM `HostPlacementAnalysis`
GROUP BY
  `Host`, `Placement`
ORDER BY
  `Host`, `Placement`;
db_sql:
WITH `HostPlacementAnalysis` AS (
  SELECT col8, '1st Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col8, '2nd Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col8, '3rd Place' AS `Placement` FROM `table_1_1149495_1`
)
SELECT
  col8,
  `Placement`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Placement_Count`,
  ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / SUM(COUNT(*)) OVER (PARTITION BY col8), 2) AS `Distribution_Percentage`
FROM `HostPlacementAnalysis`
GROUP BY
  col8, `Placement`
ORDER BY
  col8, `Placement`;

nl: Please provide a consolidated summary that segments players by profile. For each segment, I need to see the total player count, the mean age at death, and the average goal-to-cap ratio, presenting the group with the shorter lifespan first.
sql:
SELECT
  `Player Profile`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Number of Players`,
  AVG(`Age at Death`) AS `Average Age at Death`,
  AVG(`number of goals` / `number of caps`) AS `Avg Goals Per Cap`
FROM (
  SELECT
    `number of caps`,
    `number of goals`,
    CASE
      WHEN `number of caps` >= 20 OR `number of goals` >= 10 THEN `High-Profile`
      ELSE `Standard-Profile`
    END AS `Player Profile`,
    (julianday(SUBSTR(`date of death†`, 7, 4) || `-` || SUBSTR(`date of death†`, 4, 2) || `-` || SUBSTR(`date of death†`, 1, 2)) - julianday(SUBSTR(`date of birth`, 7, 4) || `-` || SUBSTR(`date of birth`, 4, 2) || `-` || SUBSTR(`date of birth`, 1, 2))) / 365.25 AS `Age at Death`
  FROM
    `table_1_11585313_1`
  WHERE
    `date of death†` LIKE `__-__-____`
)
WHERE
  `Age at Death` IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY
  `Player Profile`
ORDER BY
  `Average Age at Death` ASC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  `Player Profile`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Number of Players`,
  AVG(`Age at Death`) AS `Average Age at Death`,
  AVG(CAST(col5 AS REAL) / col4) AS `Avg Goals Per Cap`
FROM (
  SELECT
    col4,
    col5,
    CASE
      WHEN col4 >= 20 OR col5 >= 10 THEN 'High-Profile'
      ELSE 'Standard-Profile'
    END AS `Player Profile`,
    (julianday(SUBSTR(col6, 7, 4) || '-' || SUBSTR(col6, 4, 2) || '-' || SUBSTR(col6, 1, 2)) - julianday(SUBSTR(col3, 7, 4) || '-' || SUBSTR(col3, 4, 2) || '-' || SUBSTR(col3, 1, 2))) / 365.25 AS `Age at Death`
  FROM
    `table_1_11585313_1`
  WHERE
    col6 LIKE '__-__-____'
)
WHERE
  `Age at Death` IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY
  `Player Profile`
ORDER BY
  `Average Age at Death` ASC;
reasoning: This is a comprehensive question that combines all the elements of the SQL query into a single, cohesive request for a summary table. A researcher would likely ask for all the data points at once to form a complete picture for their analysis.

sql: SELECT (T1.`Peak Investment Revenue` - T2.`Subsequent Investment Revenue`) * 100.0 / T2.`Subsequent Property Taxes` AS `Tax_Hike_Burden_From_Lost_Investment_Income_Pct` FROM (SELECT CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(`Investment Earnings`, `'$'`, ``), `','`, ``) AS REAL) AS `Peak Investment Revenue` FROM `table_1_11608735_3` WHERE `Year` = 2001) AS T1, (SELECT CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(`Property Taxes`, `'$'`, ``), `','`, ``) AS REAL) AS `Subsequent Property Taxes`, CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(`Investment Earnings`, `'$'`, ``), `','`, ``) AS REAL) AS `Subsequent Investment Revenue` FROM `table_1_11608735_3` WHERE `Year` = 2005) AS T2;
db_sql: SELECT (T1.`Peak Investment Revenue` - T2.`Subsequent Investment Revenue`) * 100.0 / T2.`Subsequent Property Taxes` AS `Tax_Hike_Burden_From_Lost_Investment_Income_Pct` FROM (SELECT CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(col2, '$', ''), ',', '') AS REAL) AS `Peak Investment Revenue` FROM `table_1_11608735_3` WHERE col0 = 2001) AS T1, (SELECT CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(col1, '$', ''), ',', '') AS REAL) AS `Subsequent Property Taxes`, CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(col2, '$', ''), ',', '') AS REAL) AS `Subsequent Investment Revenue` FROM `table_1_11608735_3` WHERE col0 = 2005) AS T2;
reasoning: This question is less an inquiry and more a demand for a specific piece of evidence. The phrasing is accusatory and intended to produce a single, dramatic percentage that supports his pre-written conclusion.
seeding_value: A disgraced ex-treasurer for the school district, fired after the dot-com bubble burst, who now obsessively analyzes old financial reports to prove his aggressive investment strategy was better than the subsequent 'cowardly' reliance on tax hikes. Goals: To retroactively vindicate his high-risk, high-reward financial strategy by demonstrating that his departure directly caused an unsustainable property tax burden on the community, using the data to build a 'what if' scenario for a self-published exposé. Example Queries: What was the percentage of total revenue from 'Investment Earnings' in 2001 compared to 2005, to highlight the decline of my strategy? Calculate the year-over-year percentage growth of 'Property Taxes' to show how aggressively the district shifted the burden to homeowners after I left. nl: To establish a baseline for our 'Return on Impression' model, let's run a full diagnostic. sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN `Tournament` LIKE '%Seiko%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%MONY%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%Digital%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%Merrill Lynch%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%Citizens Union%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%United Virginia Bank%' THEN 'Corporate Branded'
    WHEN `Tournament` LIKE '%Gatlin Brothers%' OR `Tournament` LIKE '%Roy Clark%' THEN 'Celebrity Endorsed'
    ELSE 'Standard/Geographic'
  END AS `Sponsorship_Type`,
  AVG(`Purse( $ )`) AS `Average_Purse`,
  AVG(`1st Prize( $ )`) AS `Average_1st_Prize`,
  AVG(CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Winner`, INSTR(`Winner`, `(`) + 1), `)`, ``) AS REAL)) AS `Average_Winner_Win_Count`
FROM
  `table_1_11622840_1`
GROUP BY
  `Sponsorship_Type`
ORDER BY
  `Average_Purse` DESC;

nl: Show me the top 5 ships by gross tonnage that entered service after 1900, whose tonnage was greater than the historical average for their specific vessel type at the time.
sql:
WITH `VesselTypeRunningAvg` AS (
  SELECT
    `Ships name`,
    `Gross Tonnage`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Entered service`, -4) AS REAL) AS `service_year`,
    AVG(`Gross Tonnage`) OVER (
      PARTITION BY `Type of Vessel`
      ORDER BY
        CAST(SUBSTR(`Entered service`, -4) AS REAL) ROWS UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
    ) AS `running_avg_tonnage`
  FROM
    `table_1_11662133_1`
)
SELECT
  `Ships name`,
  `Gross Tonnage`
FROM
  `VesselTypeRunningAvg`
WHERE
  `service_year` > 1900 AND `Gross Tonnage` > `running_avg_tonnage`
ORDER BY
  `Gross Tonnage` DESC
LIMIT
  5;
db_sql:
WITH `VesselTypeRunningAvg` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col3,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col1, -4) AS REAL) AS `service_year`,
    AVG(col3) OVER (
      PARTITION BY col4
      ORDER BY
        CAST(SUBSTR(col1, -4) AS REAL) ROWS UNBOUNDED PRECEDING
    ) AS `running_avg_tonnage`
  FROM
    `table_1_11662133_1`
)
SELECT
  col0,
  col3
FROM
  `VesselTypeRunningAvg`
WHERE
  `service_year` > 1900 AND col3 > `running_avg_tonnage`
ORDER BY
  col3 DESC
LIMIT
  5;
reasoning:
1. Parse SQL Intent: The query identifies the top 5 ships by gross tonnage. The selection is filtered to ships that entered service after 1900 and whose tonnage exceeds the running average for their specific vessel type up to their service year. The final list is ordered by tonnage in descending order.
2. Map to Schema: The query uses 'Ships name', 'Gross Tonnage', 'Entered service' (year), and 'Type of Vessel'.
3. Draft Question: A direct, formal question is drafted to request the top 5 ships based on these criteria.
4. Validate: The question covers the top 5 limit, the descending tonnage order, the post-1900 service date, and the comparison against the running average for the vessel type.

    ELSE `Third place`
  END AS `Team`
FROM

  OR `Top scorer` LIKE '%' || `Third place` || '%';

  col4 LIKE '%' || col2 || '%'
  OR col4 LIKE '%' || col3 || '%';

nl: What is the count of players from high schools in Georgia or Tennessee, broken down by state and position type (infield vs. other)? Please rank these combinations by the number of players in descending order.
sql:
SELECT
  SUBSTR(`Hometown`, INSTR(`Hometown`, ',') + 2) AS `State`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Position` LIKE `%Infielder%`
    THEN `Infield`
    ELSE `Other`
  END AS `Position_Group`,
  COUNT(`Player`) AS `Player_Count`
FROM `table_1_11677100_16`
WHERE
  `School` LIKE `%High School%` AND (`Hometown` LIKE `%, GA` OR `Hometown` LIKE `%, TN`)
GROUP BY
  `State`,
  `Position_Group`
HAVING
  COUNT(`Player`) > 0
ORDER BY
  `Player_Count` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, ',') + 2) AS `State`,
  CASE
    WHEN col1 LIKE '%Infielder%'
    THEN 'Infield'
    ELSE 'Other'
  END AS `Position_Group`,
  COUNT(col0) AS `Player_Count`
FROM `table_1_11677100_16`
WHERE
  col2 LIKE '%High School%' AND (col3 LIKE '%, GA' OR col3 LIKE '%, TN')
GROUP BY
  `State`,
  `Position_Group`
ORDER BY
  `Player_Count` DESC;
reasoning: This version is structured as a direct 'What is...' question, focusing on the final calculated value (the count). It explicitly mentions the dimensions for the breakdown ('state and position type') and the ranking method ('descending order'), which accurately reflects the query's grouping and sorting operations.

nl: I need a full breakdown of the '11 recruiting map. Focus on the real talent pipelines—states with multiple All-Americans. For each one, show me our player count and a rundown of all the schools they signed with. Put the heaviest hitters at the top.

db_sql: SELECT SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, ',') + 2) AS `State`, COUNT(col0) AS `NumberOfPlayers`, GROUP_CONCAT(col4) AS `RecruitingColleges` FROM `table_1_11677691_5` GROUP BY `State` HAVING COUNT(col0) > 1 ORDER BY `NumberOfPlayers` DESC;
reasoning: This question is framed as a request for a comprehensive report, using persona-specific jargon like 'talent pipelines' and 'All-Americans'. It combines all elements of the SQL query into a single, efficient request for a data analyst.

nl: For each state, excluding Indiana, that has had more than one player of the year, list the state along with the names of the first and most recent players to receive the award.
sql: WITH StateHonors AS (SELECT SUBSTR(`Hometown`, -2) AS `State`, MIN(`Year`) AS `FirstYear`, MAX(`Year`) AS `LastYear` FROM `table_1_11677760_1` GROUP BY `State` HAVING COUNT(*) > 1) SELECT s.`State`, p1.`Player` AS `FirstHonoree`, p2.`Player` AS `LastHonoree` FROM StateHonors AS s JOIN `table_1_11677760_1` AS p1 ON SUBSTR(p1.`Hometown`, -2) = s.`State` AND p1.`Year` = s.`FirstYear` JOIN `table_1_11677760_1` AS p2 ON SUBSTR(p2.`Hometown`, -2) = s.`State` AND p2.`Year` = s.`LastYear` WHERE s.`State` IS NOT `IN` ORDER BY s.`State` ASC;
db_sql: WITH StateHonors AS (SELECT SUBSTR(col3, -2) AS `State`, MIN(col0) AS `FirstYear`, MAX(col0) AS `LastYear` FROM `table_1_11677760_1` GROUP BY `State` HAVING COUNT(*) > 1) SELECT s.`State`, p1.col1 AS `FirstHonoree`, p2.col1 AS `LastHonoree` FROM StateHonors s JOIN `table_1_11677760_1` p1 ON (SUBSTR(p1.col3, -2), p1.col0) = (s.`State`, s.`FirstYear`) JOIN `table_1_11677760_1` p2 ON (SUBSTR(p2.col3, -2), p2.col0) = (s.`State`, s.`LastYear`) WHERE s.`State` <> 'IN' ORDER BY s.`State` ASC;

nl: Which group of players taller than 6'7" is more positionally versatile: those from Croatia, Venezuela, or Greece, or those from college? sql: SELECT CASE WHEN `School/Club Team/Country` IN (`Croatia`, `Venezuela`, `Greece`) THEN `International` ELSE `College` END AS `Origin`, COUNT(DISTINCT `Position`) AS `VersatilityScore` FROM `table_1_11734041_18` WHERE CAST(SUBSTR(`Height in Ft.`, 1, 1) AS INTEGER) * 12 + CAST(SUBSTR(`Height in Ft.`, 3) AS INTEGER) > 79 GROUP BY `Origin` HAVING `VersatilityScore` > 1 ORDER BY `VersatilityScore` DESC;

reasoning: This version poses a direct comparative question ('Which group... is more positionally versatile?'). It defines 'versatility' as the 'count the unique positions they played', directly mapping to the query's aggregation. nl: Okay, put it all together for my final case file. Give me a master list with each episode, its air date, the chaotic timeslot they gave it, the *previous* episode's slot for comparison, and then the brutal percentage drops in both viewers and share that resulted.
sql:
WITH `CleanedData` AS (
  SELECT
    `#`,
    `Episode`,
    `Air Date`,
    `Timeslot`,
    `Share`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Viewers`, 1, INSTR(`Viewers`, ' ') - 1) AS REAL) AS `Viewers_Millions`
  FROM `table_1_11753080_2`
)
SELECT
  `current`.`Episode`,
  `current`.`Air Date`,
  `current`.`Timeslot` AS `Chaotic_Timeslot`,
  LAG(`current`.`Timeslot`, 1, `N/A`) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.`#`) AS `Previous_Timeslot`,
  printf('%.2f%%', (`current`.`Viewers_Millions` - LAG(`current`.`Viewers_Millions`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.`#`)) * 100.0 / LAG(`current`.`Viewers_Millions`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.`#`)) AS `Viewer_Change`,
  printf('%.2f%%', (`current`.`Share` - LAG(`current`.`Share`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.`#`)) * 100.0 / LAG(`current`.`Share`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.`#`)) AS `Share_Change`
FROM `CleanedData` AS `current`
ORDER BY `current`.`#`;
db_sql:
WITH `CleanedData` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col1,
    col2,
    col3,
    col5,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col7, 1, INSTR(col7, ' ') - 1) AS REAL) AS `Viewers_Millions`
  FROM `table_1_11753080_2`
)
SELECT
  `current`.col1,
  `current`.col2,
  `current`.col3 AS `Chaotic_Timeslot`,
  LAG(`current`.col3, 1, 'N/A') OVER (ORDER BY `current`.col0) AS `Previous_Timeslot`,
  printf('%.2f%%', (`current`.`Viewers_Millions` - LAG(`current`.`Viewers_Millions`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.col0)) * 100.0 / LAG(`current`.`Viewers_Millions`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.col0)) AS `Viewer_Change`,
  printf('%.2f%%', (`current`.col5 - LAG(`current`.col5, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.col0)) * 100.0 / LAG(`current`.col5, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `current`.col0)) AS `Share_Change`
FROM `CleanedData` AS `current`
ORDER BY `current`.col0;
reasoning: This is the writer's ultimate goal: to consolidate all the individual pieces of evidence into a single, comprehensive report. They see this combined data as the 'smoking gun' that will finally vindicate them.
seeding_value: A disgraced television writer from the late 2000s, obsessively analyzing the ratings of their failed sitcom 'Unhitched' to prove their avant-garde episode titles were sabotaged by poor network scheduling. Goals: To build a forensic case against the network, proving that the constant timeslot changes—especially the disastrous back-to-back airing on March 23rd—were the true cause of the show's demise, ultimately seeking personal and creative vindication. Example Queries: What was the exact percentage drop in viewers and the key 18-49 demographic when the show was moved from its 10:00 P.M. premiere slot to 9:30 P.M.? Isolate the ratings for the two episodes aired on March 23rd to demonstrate how splitting the audience across different timeslots in a single night was the final nail in the coffin. nl: For each cylinder arrangement, what is the fastest model with a top speed over 200 km/h? Show the model, its top speed, and its technology era based on its production start year, listed from fastest to slowest.
sql: WITH `RankedModels` AS (SELECT `model`, `top speed (km/h)`, CAST(SUBSTR(`production period`, 1, 4) AS INTEGER) AS `start_year`, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY SUBSTR(`cylinders/ valves`, 1, 3) ORDER BY `top speed (km/h)` DESC) AS `rank_in_type` FROM `table_1_1176162_3`) SELECT r.`model`, r.`top speed (km/h)`, CASE WHEN r.`start_year` < 2000 THEN `'90s Tech'` WHEN r.`start_year` BETWEEN 2000 AND 2002 THEN `'Early 2000s'` ELSE `'Late 2000s'` END AS `TechEra` FROM `RankedModels` AS r WHERE r.`rank_in_type` = 1 AND EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `table_1_1176162_3` AS t WHERE t.`model` IS r.`model` AND t.`top speed (km/h)` > 200) ORDER BY r.`top speed (km/h)` DESC;
db_sql: WITH `RankedModels` AS (SELECT col0, col6, CAST(SUBSTR(col7, 1, 4) AS INTEGER) AS `start_year`, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY SUBSTR(col1, 1, 3) ORDER BY col6 DESC) AS `rank_in_type` FROM `table_1_1176162_3`) SELECT r.col0, r.col6, CASE WHEN r.`start_year` < 2000 THEN '90s Tech' WHEN r.`start_year` BETWEEN 2000 AND 2002 THEN 'Early 2000s' ELSE 'Late 2000s' END AS `TechEra` FROM `RankedModels` AS r WHERE r.`rank_in_type` = 1 AND EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM `table_1_1176162_3` AS t WHERE t.col0 IS r.col0 AND t.col6 > 200) ORDER BY r.col6 DESC;
reasoning: This question breaks down the request logically. It first establishes the grouping criteria ('for each cylinder arrangement'), then the ranking and filtering criteria ('the fastest model that can go over 200 km/h'). Finally, it specifies the desired output columns, including the calculated 'TechEra', and the final sorting order, fully encapsulating the query's intent.

db_sql: SELECT col3, MIN(col1) AS `Format Start Date`, COUNT(*) AS `Number of Releases`, AVG(col5) AS `Avg Episodes per Release`, AVG((CAST(SUBSTR(col4, 1, INSTR(col4, 'h') - 1) AS REAL) * 60 + CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, 's ') + 2), ' minutes', '') AS REAL)) / col6) AS `Avg Minutes per Disc` FROM `table_1_1180228_1` GROUP BY col3 ORDER BY `Format Start Date`;

Goals: To pinpoint the exact moment this series 'went widescreen' and analyze if this technological upgrade coincided with changes in content density or thematic scope, providing evidence for a dissertation on 'The Anamorphic Framing of the Bucolic Ideal'. nl: Can we disaggregate the 2007-08 incoming cohort by their mode of acquisition—that is, market transfers versus internal promotions—and for each of these two streams, quantify the number of individuals, their mean age upon entry, the total capital outlay in millions of euros, and the proportional representation of EU-status labor?
sql: SELECT CASE `Type` WHEN `Transfer` THEN `Acquired Externally` WHEN `Promote` THEN `Promoted Internally` END AS `Talent_Source`, COUNT(*) AS `Number_of_Players`, AVG(`Age`) AS `Average_Age_at_Acquisition`, SUM(CASE WHEN `Transfer fee` = `Youth system` THEN 0 ELSE CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Transfer fee`, 2, INSTR(`Transfer fee`, `M`) - 2), `+`, ` `) AS REAL) END) AS `Total_Capital_Outlay_Millions_EUR`, AVG(CASE WHEN `EU` = `EU` THEN 1.0 ELSE 0.0 END) * 100 AS `Percentage_EU_Status` FROM `table_1_11891841_2` GROUP BY `Talent_Source` ORDER BY `Total_Capital_Outlay_Millions_EUR` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT CASE col6 WHEN 'Transfer' THEN 'Acquired Externally' WHEN 'Promote' THEN 'Promoted Internally' END AS `Talent_Source`, COUNT(*) AS `Number_of_Players`, AVG(col5) AS `Average_Age_at_Acquisition`, SUM(CASE WHEN col10 = 'Youth system' THEN 0 ELSE CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col10, 2, INSTR(col10, 'M') - 2), '+', ' ') AS REAL) END) AS `Total_Capital_Outlay_Millions_EUR`, AVG(CASE WHEN col3 = 'EU' THEN 1.0 ELSE 0.0 END) * 100 AS `Percentage_EU_Status` FROM `table_1_11891841_2` GROUP BY `Talent_Source` ORDER BY `Total_Capital_Outlay_Millions_EUR` DESC;
reasoning: This persona views player acquisition through a socio-economic lens, seeing two distinct pathways: capital-intensive market acquisition and internal pipeline development. This overarching question seeks a comparative summary of these two 'talent streams' based on the key metrics for their analysis.
seeding_value: A historical sociologist specializing in the micro-economies of high-skill labor migration, using elite football squads as case studies for globalization. Goals: To publish a paper analyzing the 2007-08 FC Barcelona transfer window as a microcosm of global talent flow, contrasting the high-cost acquisition of established foreign assets with the 'zero-cost' promotion of localized, homegrown talent. Example Queries: What is the ratio of EU to Non-EU players acquired, and how does their average transfer fee differ? Calculate the total capital spent on acquiring talent from foreign leagues versus the 'investment' in youth players from the club's own system. What is the average age of a player acquired via 'Transfer' compared to one acquired via 'Promote', and what does this suggest about the club's strategy for immediate impact versus future potential?

nl: To assess supplier experience from the 2007 releases, please create a report on the complex printing jobs. Show me a count of stamps produced by each design firm and paper type combination where the process involved foil, embossing, or intaglio, ordered to show the most experienced pairs first.
sql: SELECT `Design`, `Paper Type`, COUNT(*) AS `Specialized_Print_Runs` FROM `table_1_11900773_5` WHERE `Printing Process` LIKE `%foil%` OR `Printing Process` LIKE `%embossing%` OR `Printing Process` LIKE `%intaglio%` GROUP BY `Design`, `Paper Type` ORDER BY `Specialized_Print_Runs` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col3, col6, COUNT(*) AS `Specialized_Print_Runs` FROM `table_1_11900773_5` WHERE col5 LIKE '%foil%' OR col5 LIKE '%embossing%' OR col5 LIKE '%intaglio%' GROUP BY col3, col6 ORDER BY `Specialized_Print_Runs` DESC;

It uses phrasing like 'complex printing jobs' and 'supplier experience' to clearly state the business purpose behind the query, showing they are analyzing past performance to inform future strategy.

nl: Could you prepare the final composition guide for me? I need to see a complete list with each child's full name, their name's meaning, their birth weight, and their assigned musical motif, all sorted from the lightest baby to the heaviest to map out the symphony's full progression.
sql:
SELECT
  `Full Name`,
  `Meaning`,
  `Weight at birth`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Meaning` LIKE '%Strength%' THEN 'Cello Theme (Strength)'
    WHEN `Meaning` LIKE '%God holds%' THEN 'Harp Theme (Protection)'
    WHEN `Meaning` LIKE '%God is%' THEN 'Flute Theme (Presence)'
    ELSE 'Violin Theme (Journey)'
  END AS `Musical Motif`,
  CAST(SUBSTR(`Weight at birth`, 1, INSTR(`Weight at birth`, 'g') - 1) AS REAL) AS `WeightInGrams`
FROM `table_1_11908801_1`
ORDER BY
  `WeightInGrams`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col0,
  col4,
  col3,
  CASE
    WHEN col4 LIKE '%Strength%' THEN 'Cello Theme (Strength)'
    WHEN col4 LIKE '%God holds%' THEN 'Harp Theme (Protection)'
    WHEN col4 LIKE '%God is%' THEN 'Flute Theme (Presence)'
    ELSE 'Violin Theme (Journey)'
  END AS `Musical Motif`,
  CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, 'g') - 1) AS REAL) AS `WeightInGrams`
FROM `table_1_11908801_1`
ORDER BY
  `WeightInGrams`;

Goals: To compose a seven-part 'Symphony of Survival' for the Chukwu octuplets, where each child's name meaning informs the lyrical theme and their birth weight dictates the tempo and dynamics, creating a musical narrative of their unique identity from the moment of birth. nl: For each first-class team that includes at least one player born before 1970, how many of their players were born in 1970 or later? Please show the teams and their player counts in descending order.
sql: WITH `VeteranTeams` AS (SELECT DISTINCT `First Class Team` FROM `table_1_11950720_3` WHERE substr(`Date of Birth`, -4) < `1970`) SELECT T1.`First Class Team`, COUNT(T1.`Player`) FROM `table_1_11950720_3` AS `T1` INNER JOIN `VeteranTeams` ON T1.`First Class Team` = `VeteranTeams`.`First Class Team` WHERE substr(T1.`Date of Birth`, -4) >= `1970` GROUP BY T1.`First Class Team` HAVING COUNT(T1.`Player`) > 0 ORDER BY COUNT(T1.`Player`) DESC;
db_sql: SELECT T1.col5, COUNT(T1.col1) FROM `table_1_11950720_3` AS T1 WHERE T1.col5 IN (SELECT col5 FROM `table_1_11950720_3` WHERE SUBSTR(col2, -4) < '1970') AND SUBSTR(T1.col2, -4) >= '1970' GROUP BY T1.col5 ORDER BY COUNT(T1.col1) DESC;
reasoning: This question directly translates the query's logic by first specifying the condition for selecting the teams (having players born before 1970) and then stating the counting criteria for players within those teams (born 1970 or later). It concludes by requesting the results be sorted, mirroring the ORDER BY clause.

nl: How many fast and fast-medium bowlers come from each first-class team? List the teams, starting with the one that has the smallest number of these bowlers.
sql: SELECT `First Class Team`, COUNT(*) AS `Pace_Bowler_Count` FROM `table_1_11950720_5` WHERE `Bowling Style` IN (`Right arm fast`, `Left arm fast`, `Right arm fast-medium`) GROUP BY `First Class Team` ORDER BY `Pace_Bowler_Count`;
db_sql: SELECT col5, count(*) FROM `table_1_11950720_5` WHERE col4 LIKE '%fast%' OR col4 LIKE '%medium%' GROUP BY col5 ORDER BY count(*) DESC;
