The SQL's `WHERE` clause is interpreted by explicitly mentioning 'fast and fast-medium bowlers'. The `GROUP BY` and `COUNT` are phrased as 'How many... does each first-class team have?'. The `ORDER BY` clause is translated into a simple instruction for how to display the results.

nl: To prepare for my paper, can you provide a summary table showing how many specialist pace versus spin bowlers fall into each birth-season profile? Also, include the average age for each distinct group so I can analyze the relationship between chrono-development and athletic longevity in that squad.
sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN `Date of Birth` LIKE '%April%' OR `Date of Birth` LIKE '%May%' OR `Date of Birth` LIKE '%June%' THEN 'Q2 (Early-Mid Year Growth)'
    WHEN `Date of Birth` LIKE '%July%' OR `Date of Birth` LIKE '%August%' OR `Date of Birth` LIKE '%September%' THEN 'Q3 (Mid-Late Year Growth)'
    ELSE 'Off-Peak Season'
  END AS `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Bowling Style` LIKE '%fast%' OR `Bowling Style` LIKE '%medium%' THEN 'Pace Bowler'
    WHEN `Bowling Style` LIKE '%spin%' OR `Bowling Style` LIKE '%break%' THEN 'Spin Bowler'
    ELSE 'Non-Specialist'
  END AS `Kinetic_Action_Type`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Player_Count`,
  CAST(AVG(1998 - SUBSTR(`Date of Birth`, -4, 4)) AS INTEGER) AS `Approx_Avg_Age_In_1998`
FROM `table_1_11950720_8`
WHERE `Kinetic_Action_Type` != 'Non-Specialist'
GROUP BY
  `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  `Kinetic_Action_Type`
ORDER BY
  `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  `Kinetic_Action_Type`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN col2 LIKE '%April%' OR col2 LIKE '%May%' OR col2 LIKE '%June%' THEN 'Q2 (Early-Mid Year Growth)'
    WHEN col2 LIKE '%July%' OR col2 LIKE '%August%' OR col2 LIKE '%September%' THEN 'Q3 (Mid-Late Year Growth)'
    ELSE 'Off-Peak Season'
  END AS `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  CASE
    WHEN col4 LIKE '%fast%' OR col4 LIKE '%medium%' THEN 'Pace Bowler'
    WHEN col4 LIKE '%spin%' OR col4 LIKE '%break%' THEN 'Spin Bowler'
    ELSE 'Non-Specialist'
  END AS `Kinetic_Action_Type`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Player_Count`,
  CAST(AVG(1998 - SUBSTR(col2, -4, 4)) AS INTEGER) AS `Approx_Avg_Age_In_1998`
FROM `table_1_11950720_8`
WHERE `Kinetic_Action_Type` != 'Non-Specialist'
GROUP BY
  `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  `Kinetic_Action_Type`
ORDER BY
  `Birth_Season_Profile`,
  `Kinetic_Action_Type`;

Goals: To retroactively analyze the 1998 West Indies squad to find correlations between birth dates and specific bowling actions (e.g., 'fast' vs. 'spin'), aiming to publish a controversial paper on 'Chrono-Kinetic Profiling' in cricket. nl: To model their cohesion deficits, I need a specific data set. Give me a breakdown of every game where Pierce or Garnett's individual output overshadowed the team's, meaning they led in points plus either rebounds or assists. I need to see the game, the full stat leader breakdown, and the final margin of victory for each of those occurrences.
sql: SELECT `Game`, `Score`, `High points`, `High rebounds`, `High assists`, (CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, 1, INSTR(`Score`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(REPLACE(`Score`, ' (OT)', ''), INSTR(`Score`, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) AS `Point_Differential` FROM `table_1_11959669_3` WHERE (`High points` LIKE '%Garnett%' AND (`High rebounds` LIKE '%Garnett%' OR `High assists` LIKE '%Garnett%')) OR (`High points` LIKE '%Pierce%' AND (`High rebounds` LIKE '%Pierce%' OR `High assists` LIKE '%Pierce%'));
db_sql: SELECT col0, col3, col4, col5, col6, (CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(REPLACE(col3, ' (OT)', ''), INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) AS `Point_Differential` FROM `table_1_11959669_3` WHERE (col4 LIKE '%Garnett%' AND (col5 LIKE '%Garnett%' OR col6 LIKE '%Garnett%')) OR (col4 LIKE '%Pierce%' AND (col5 LIKE '%Pierce%' OR col6 LIKE '%Pierce%'));
reasoning: This is a more direct and analytical framing, focusing on the relationship between leadership distribution and game outcome. The persona is treating player stats as input variables for the predictive model he wants to build.
seeding_value: An organizational psychologist turned 'Team Synergy Consultant' who believes that the distribution of on-court statistical leadership directly reflects a superteam's internal chemistry and vulnerability. Goals: To develop a predictive model that identifies which patterns of statistical dominance among the Celtics' stars (Garnett, Pierce, Allen) correlate with narrower victory margins or losses, in order to advise rival teams on how to disrupt their cohesion. Example Queries: Identify all games where a single player was the high performer in two or more categories (points, rebounds, assists) and check the final score margin. Compare the distribution of the 'High points' leader between Garnett, Pierce, and Allen in games won by more than 10 points versus games won by less than 10 points. List the primary assist leader for every game where Paul Pierce was the high-point scorer to see who is facilitating his success.

nl: Show me a ranking of players based on the number of times they were the top assister in high-scoring or close games. For this, high-scoring means over 110 points, and a close game is one decided by 10 points or less.
sql: SELECT `High assists` AS `Playmaker`, COUNT(`Game`) AS `Impact_Games` FROM `table_1_11959669_6` WHERE CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, 1, INSTR(`Score`, '–') - 1) AS INTEGER) > 110 OR CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, 1, INSTR(`Score`, '–') - 1) AS INTEGER) - CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, INSTR(`Score`, '–') + 1) AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 1 AND 10 GROUP BY `Playmaker` ORDER BY `Impact_Games` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col6 AS `Playmaker`, COUNT(col0) AS `Impact_Games` FROM `table_1_11959669_6` WHERE CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS INTEGER) > 110 OR CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS INTEGER) - CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 1 AND 10 GROUP BY `Playmaker` ORDER BY `Impact_Games` DESC;
reasoning: This question frames the request as a task to generate a ranking. It simplifies the game conditions into descriptive terms ('high-scoring' and 'close') and then defines them, mirroring the WHERE clause. The core request is to rank players by the count of games where they were the 'top assister', which perfectly matches the SELECT, GROUP BY, and ORDER BY clauses.

db_sql: SELECT COUNT(col0), AVG(CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) FROM table_1_11959669_7 WHERE col4 LIKE '`Garnett (%)`' AND col4 NOT LIKE '`%,%`' AND col5 LIKE '`Garnett (%)`' AND col5 NOT LIKE '`%,%`';
reasoning: This question frames the data request within the context of building predictive models, a core task for an oddsmaker. It uses professional, analytical language like 'sharpen our models', 'scoring margin', and 'sample size' to reflect the persona's data-driven approach.

nl: Generate a list of playoff games starting from the third one, ordered by game number. For each game, display its date, score, and a performance category labeled 'Key Player High Scorer' if Iguodala had the most points, otherwise label it 'Other Player High Scorer'.
sql:
SELECT
  `Date`,
  `Score`,
  CASE
    WHEN `High points` LIKE '`Iguodala%`'
    THEN '`Key Player High Scorer`'
    ELSE '`Other Player High Scorer`'
  END AS `Performance_Category`
FROM `table_1_11960196_3`
WHERE `Game` > 2
ORDER BY `Game`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col1,
  col3,

sql:
SELECT
  `Game`,
  `Team`,
  CASE
    WHEN SUBSTR(`High points`, 1, INSTR(`High points`, ' (') - 1) = SUBSTR(`High assists`, 1, INSTR(`High assists`, ' (') - 1)
    THEN `Playmaker MVP`
    WHEN SUBSTR(`High points`, 1, INSTR(`High points`, ' (') - 1) = SUBSTR(`High rebounds`, 1, INSTR(`High rebounds`, ' (') - 1)
    THEN `Dominant MVP`
    ELSE `Scoring Leader`
  END AS `Game Impact`
FROM
  `table_1_11964154_11`
WHERE
  `Score` LIKE `W %`
ORDER BY
  `Game` ASC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col2, CASE WHEN SUBSTR(col4, 1, INSTR(col4, ' (') - 1) = SUBSTR(col6, 1, INSTR(col6, ' (') - 1) THEN 'Playmaker MVP' WHEN SUBSTR(col4, 1, INSTR(col4, ' (') - 1) = SUBSTR(col5, 1, INSTR(col5, ' (') - 1) THEN 'Dominant MVP' ELSE 'Scoring Leader' END AS `Game Impact` FROM `table_1_11964154_11` WHERE col3 LIKE 'W %' ORDER BY col0 ASC;
reasoning: This question directly translates the query's logic into a detailed request. It specifies filtering for wins (`WHERE Score LIKE 'W %'`), the columns to display (`Game`, `Team`), the complex conditional logic (`CASE` statement) with its specific labels, and the sorting requirement (`ORDER BY Game ASC`). The phrasing is clear and comprehensive, capturing every component of the SQL.

nl: I'm looking for a pattern of underperformance when fan support was highest. Generate a report of all KeyArena losses where we had a bigger-than-usual crowd, and give me the game stats so I can see who wasn't pulling their weight.
sql: SELECT `Date`, `Team` AS `Opponent`, `Score`, `High points`, `High rebounds`, `High assists`, `Location Attendance` FROM `table_1_11964154_7` WHERE `Score` LIKE 'L %' AND `Location Attendance` LIKE 'KeyArena%' AND CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Location Attendance`, INSTR(`Location Attendance`, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER) > (SELECT AVG(CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Location Attendance`, INSTR(`Location Attendance`, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER)) FROM `table_1_11964154_7` WHERE `Location Attendance` LIKE 'KeyArena%') ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Location Attendance`, INSTR(`Location Attendance`, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER) DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col1, col2 AS `Opponent`, col3, col4, col5, col6, col7 FROM `table_1_11964154_7` WHERE col3 LIKE 'L %' AND col7 LIKE 'KeyArena%' AND CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col7, INSTR(col7, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER) > (SELECT AVG(CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col7, INSTR(col7, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER)) FROM `table_1_11964154_7` WHERE col7 LIKE 'KeyArena%') ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col7, INSTR(col7, ' ') + 1), ',', '') AS INTEGER) DESC;
reasoning: The persona is using investigative language to build a narrative of intentional failure. They are looking for a 'pattern of sabotage' by cross-referencing high fan engagement with poor team performance on the court.
seeding_value: A forensic accountant hired by the 'Save Our Sonics' fan coalition to find statistical evidence of 'corporate sabotage' during the team's final season, believing the new ownership intentionally tanked team performance to justify relocation. Goals: To build a case by identifying statistical anomalies, such as poor performance in high-attendance home games or unusual player stat correlations, suggesting a deliberate effort to demoralize the Seattle fan base and suppress ticket revenue. nl: Where's the biggest performance gap? Let's compare our game count and average scoring margin for wins and losses, contrasting our home performance with our away performance to find the core story.
sql:
SELECT
  CASE WHEN `Team` LIKE '@%' THEN 'Away' ELSE 'Home' END AS `Location`,
  CASE WHEN CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, 1, INSTR(`Score`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) > CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, INSTR(`Score`, '–') + 1) AS REAL) THEN 'Win' ELSE 'Loss' END AS `Result`,
  COUNT(`Game`) AS `Games_Played`,
  AVG(CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, 1, INSTR(`Score`, '–') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(`Score`, INSTR(`Score`, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) AS `Avg_Point_Differential`
FROM
  `table_1_11964263_13`
GROUP BY
  `Location`, `Result`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  CASE WHEN col2 LIKE '@%' THEN 'Away' ELSE 'Home' END AS `Location`,
  CASE WHEN CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) > CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL) THEN 'Win' ELSE 'Loss' END AS `Result`,
  COUNT(col0) AS `Games_Played`,
  AVG(CAST(SUBSTR(col3, 1, INSTR(col3, '–') - 1) AS REAL) - CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '–') + 1) AS REAL)) AS `Avg_Point_Differential`
FROM
  `table_1_11964263_13`
GROUP BY
  `Location`, `Result`;
reasoning: This question is phrased to directly find the most compelling contrast in the data. The strategist wants to identify the most dramatic performance split to use as the central conflict or turning point in their story.

They are researching memorable playoff series from the late 2000s to find compelling narratives for a new content series. Goals: To analyze individual player performances and the impact of game location on outcomes during the 2008 Jazz vs. Rockets playoff series, in order to build a story around key turning points. Example Queries: For which games was Deron Williams the leader in both points and assists? What was the Jazz's record and average margin of victory/defeat in home games versus away games? Who was the high rebounder in each of the Jazz's wins?

nl: For the Fort Lauderdale Strikers, what was their season highlight for each year after 1990 where they did not enter the Open Cup? For the year 1991, show their regular season result, but for all other years, show their playoffs result. Please present the information in reverse chronological order.
sql:
SELECT
  `Year`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Year` = 1991 THEN `Reg. Season`
    ELSE `Playoffs`
  END AS `Season_Highlight`
FROM
  `table_1_12002388_1`
WHERE
  `Year` > 1990 AND `Open Cup` = `Did not enter`
ORDER BY
  `Year` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col0,
  CASE
    WHEN col0 = 1991 THEN col3
    ELSE col4
  END AS `Season_Highlight`
FROM
  `table_1_12002388_1`
WHERE
  col0 > 1990 AND col4 <> 'Did not qualify'
ORDER BY
  col0 DESC;
reasoning: This reasoning parses the SQL query's intent by breaking it down into its core components. It identifies the target columns (Year and a conditional 'Season_Highlight'), the filtering criteria (Year > 1990 and Open Cup status), and the sorting order (descending by Year). The question is then drafted to be a direct, comprehensive request that explicitly states all these conditions, including the special case for the year 1991, ensuring all aspects of the query are covered in a formal manner.

nl: To calibrate the Synergy Index, pull the data on all repeat-win partnerships across the three doubles disciplines. For each pair, I need the following metrics: total championships won, the durational success window in years, and the specific start and end years of that period. Sort the output to show the most prolific pairs first, using staying power as the secondary ranking factor.
sql:
WITH `AllDoublesWins` AS (
  SELECT `Year`, `Mens doubles` AS `Pair`, 'Mens Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Womens doubles` AS `Pair`, 'Womens Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Mixed doubles` AS `Pair`, 'Mixed Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
)
SELECT
  `Pair`,
  `Discipline`,
  COUNT(`Pair`) AS `Total_Titles`,
  MAX(`Year`) - MIN(`Year`) AS `Dominance_Span_Years`,
  MIN(`Year`) AS `First_Title_Year`,
  MAX(`Year`) AS `Last_Title_Year`
FROM `AllDoublesWins`
GROUP BY
  `Pair`,
  `Discipline`
HAVING
  `Total_Titles` > 1
ORDER BY
  `Total_Titles` DESC,
  `Dominance_Span_Years` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `AllDoublesWins` AS (
  SELECT col0, col3 AS `Pair`, 'Mens Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col4 AS `Pair`, 'Womens Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col5 AS `Pair`, 'Mixed Doubles' AS `Discipline` FROM `table_1_12027364_1`
)
SELECT
  `Pair`,
  `Discipline`,
  COUNT(`Pair`) AS `Total_Titles`,
  MAX(col0) - MIN(col0) AS `Dominance_Span_Years`,
  MIN(col0) AS `First_Title_Year`,
  MAX(col0) AS `Last_Title_Year`
FROM `AllDoublesWins`
GROUP BY
  `Pair`,
  `Discipline`
HAVING
  `Total_Titles` > 1
ORDER BY
  `Total_Titles` DESC,
  `Dominance_Span_Years` DESC;

nl: What are the titles of all episodes and what is the role of their director? Consider Jeff Melman and Jack Kenny to be 'Core Directors' and all others to be 'Guest Directors', then sort the results from the last episode to the first.
sql:
SELECT
  `Title`,
  CASE `Directed by`
    WHEN `Jeff Melman`
    THEN `Core Director`
    WHEN `Jack Kenny`
    THEN `Core Director`
    ELSE `Guest Director`
  END AS `Director Role`
FROM
  `table_1_12033013_1`
ORDER BY
  `No. in series` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col1, CASE WHEN col2 IN ('Jeff Melman', 'Jack Kenny') THEN 'Core Director' ELSE 'Guest Director' END AS `Director Role` FROM `table_1_12033013_1`;

nl: Show me the five years where the nation's spirit either soared or plummeted the most. I want to see when the change in birth rate and the change in death rate were most wildly out of sync with each other.
sql:
WITH YearlyRateChanges AS (
  SELECT
    `` AS `Year`,
    CAST(`Crude birth rate (per 1000)` AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(`Crude birth rate (per 1000)` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY ``) AS `BirthRateShift`,
    CAST(`Crude death rate (per 1000)` AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(`Crude death rate (per 1000)` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY ``) AS `DeathRateShift`
  FROM
    `table_1_12060_2`
)
SELECT
  `Year`,
  `BirthRateShift`,
  `DeathRateShift`,
  (`BirthRateShift` - `DeathRateShift`) AS `DemographicDivergence`
FROM
  YearlyRateChanges
WHERE
  `Year` > 1993
ORDER BY
  ABS(`DemographicDivergence`) DESC
LIMIT 5;
db_sql:
WITH YearlyRateChanges AS (
  SELECT
    col0 AS `Year`,
    CAST(col5 AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(col5 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `BirthRateShift`,
    CAST(col6 AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(col6 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY col0) AS `DeathRateShift`
  FROM
    `table_1_12060_2`
)
SELECT
  `Year`,
  `BirthRateShift`,
  `DeathRateShift`,
  (`BirthRateShift` - `DeathRateShift`) AS `DemographicDivergence`
FROM
  YearlyRateChanges
WHERE
  `Year` > 1993
ORDER BY
  ABS(`DemographicDivergence`) DESC
LIMIT 5;

nl: Let's quantify the ritualized ascent. Can you calculate the composite difficulty for each hierarchical transition—averaging the percentage increase in both evaluation standards and required lesson volume—and then rank these 'rites of passage' from the most to least arduous?
sql:
WITH `BeltProgression` AS (
  SELECT
    `` AS `Belt`,
    CAST(`Evaluation average (From February 2011)` AS REAL) AS `EvalRequirement`,
    `Peak lessons taught` AS `LessonRequirement`,
    LAG(``, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `` ASC) AS `PreviousBelt`,
    LAG(CAST(`Evaluation average (From February 2011)` AS REAL), 1) OVER (ORDER BY `` ASC) AS `PreviousEvalRequirement`,
    LAG(`Peak lessons taught`, 1) OVER (ORDER BY `` ASC) AS `PreviousLessonRequirement`
  FROM `table_1_12074447_4`
)
SELECT
  `PreviousBelt` || ` to ` || `Belt` AS `HierarchicalTransition`,
  ((`EvalRequirement` - `PreviousEvalRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousEvalRequirement`) AS `EvalHurdleIncreasePct`,
  ((`LessonRequirement` - `PreviousLessonRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousLessonRequirement`) AS `WorkVolumeHurdleIncreasePct`,
  (((`EvalRequirement` - `PreviousEvalRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousEvalRequirement`) + ((`LessonRequirement` - `PreviousLessonRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousLessonRequirement`)) / 2.0 AS `CompositeRiteOfPassageScore`
FROM
  `BeltProgression`
WHERE
  `PreviousBelt` IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  `CompositeRiteOfPassageScore` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `BeltProgression` AS (
  SELECT
    col0 AS `Belt`,
    CAST(col1 AS REAL) AS `EvalRequirement`,
    col7 AS `LessonRequirement`,
    LAG(col0, 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0 ASC) AS `PreviousBelt`,
    LAG(CAST(col1 AS REAL), 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0 ASC) AS `PreviousEvalRequirement`,
    LAG(col7, 1) OVER (ORDER BY col0 ASC) AS `PreviousLessonRequirement`
  FROM `table_1_12074447_4`
)
SELECT
  `PreviousBelt` || ' to ' || `Belt` AS `HierarchicalTransition`,
  ((`EvalRequirement` - `PreviousEvalRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousEvalRequirement`) AS `EvalHurdleIncreasePct`,
  ((`LessonRequirement` - `PreviousLessonRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousLessonRequirement`) AS `WorkVolumeHurdleIncreasePct`,
  (((`EvalRequirement` - `PreviousEvalRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousEvalRequirement`) + ((`LessonRequirement` - `PreviousLessonRequirement`) * 100.0 / `PreviousLessonRequirement`)) / 2.0 AS `CompositeRiteOfPassageScore`
FROM
  `BeltProgression`
WHERE
  `PreviousBelt` IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  `CompositeRiteOfPassageScore` DESC;

nl: Can you run a full performance summary of our key German players at the Norwegian International? I need a list of each player, their total number of titles won, and a detailed breakdown of each victory with the corresponding year and discipline. Please sort the output to show our most successful athletes at the top.
sql:
WITH `GermanPlayerWins` AS (
  SELECT `Year`, `Discipline`, `Player`
  FROM (
    SELECT `Year`, 'Mens singles' AS `Discipline`, `Mens singles` AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Year`, 'Womens singles' AS `Discipline`, `Womens singles` AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Year`, 'Mens doubles' AS `Discipline`, `Mens doubles` AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Year`, 'Womens doubles' AS `Discipline`, `Womens doubles` AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT `Year`, 'Mixed doubles' AS `Discipline`, `Mixed doubles` AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
  ) AS `Unpivoted`,
  (
    VALUES ('Juliane Schenk'), ('Michael Fuchs'), ('Ingo Kindervater'), ('Johannes Schoettler'), ('Birgit Overzier'), ('Annekatrin Lillie'), ('Marc Zwiebler'), ('Kristof Hopp'), ('Björn Joppien'), ('Petra Overzier'), ('Nicole Grether'), ('Olga Konon')
  ) AS `Players`(`Player`)
  WHERE `Unpivoted`.`Winner` LIKE '%' || `Players`.`Player` || '%'
)
SELECT
  `Player`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total_Titles`,
  GROUP_CONCAT(`Discipline` || ' (' || `Year` || ')', '; ') AS `Title_Details`
FROM `GermanPlayerWins`
GROUP BY
  `Player`
ORDER BY
  `Total_Titles` DESC,
  `Player` ASC;
db_sql:
WITH `GermanPlayerWins` AS (
  SELECT
    T1.col0,
    T1.`Discipline`,
    T2.`Player`
  FROM (
    SELECT col0, 'Mens singles' AS `Discipline`, col1 AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, 'Womens singles' AS `Discipline`, col2 AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, 'Mens doubles' AS `Discipline`, col3 AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, 'Womens doubles' AS `Discipline`, col4 AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
    UNION ALL
    SELECT col0, 'Mixed doubles' AS `Discipline`, col5 AS `Winner` FROM `table_1_12121208_1`
  ) AS T1
  JOIN (
    SELECT 'Juliane Schenk' AS `Player` UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Michael Fuchs' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Ingo Kindervater' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Johannes Schoettler' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Birgit Overzier' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Annekatrin Lillie' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Marc Zwiebler' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Kristof Hopp' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Björn Joppien' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Petra Overzier' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Nicole Grether' UNION ALL
    SELECT 'Olga Konon'
  ) AS T2
    ON T1.`Winner` LIKE '%' || T2.`Player` || '%'
)
SELECT
  `Player`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total_Titles`,
  GROUP_CONCAT(`Discipline` || ' (' || col0 || ')', '; ') AS `Title_Details`
FROM `GermanPlayerWins`
GROUP BY
  `Player`
ORDER BY
  `Total_Titles` DESC,
  `Player` ASC;

nl: Which of my on-court soulmates had a single, glorious year of triumph, winning both a singles and a mixed doubles title together, only for their partnership to vanish from the winner's circle forever after?
sql:
WITH `GoldenPairs` AS (
  SELECT
    `Year` AS `GoldenYear`,
    `Mens singles` AS `Champion`,
    `Mixed doubles` AS `Partnership`
  FROM `table_1_12171145_1`
  WHERE
    `Mixed doubles` LIKE '%' || `Mens singles` || '%'
  UNION ALL
  SELECT
    `Year` AS `GoldenYear`,
    `Womens singles` AS `Champion`,
    `Mixed doubles` AS `Partnership`
  FROM `table_1_12171145_1`
  WHERE
    `Mixed doubles` LIKE '%' || `Womens singles` || '%'
)
SELECT
  T1.`GoldenYear`,
  T1.`Champion` AS `Solo_Star`,
  TRIM(REPLACE(T1.`Partnership`, T1.`Champion`, '')) AS `Partner_In_Glory`
FROM `GoldenPairs` AS T1
LEFT JOIN `table_1_12171145_1` AS T2 ON T1.`Partnership` = T2.`Mixed doubles`
AND T2.`Year` > T1.`GoldenYear`
WHERE
  T2.`Year` IS NULL
ORDER BY
  T1.`GoldenYear`;
db_sql:
WITH `GoldenPairs` AS (
  SELECT
    col0 AS `GoldenYear`,
    col1 AS `Champion`,
    col5 AS `Partnership`
  FROM `table_1_12171145_1`
  WHERE
    col5 LIKE '%' || col1 || '%'
  UNION ALL
  SELECT
    col0 AS `GoldenYear`,
    col2 AS `Champion`,
    col5 AS `Partnership`
  FROM `table_1_12171145_1`
  WHERE
    col5 LIKE '%' || col2 || '%'
)
SELECT
  T1.`GoldenYear`,
  T1.`Champion` AS `Solo_Star`,
  TRIM(REPLACE(T1.`Partnership`, T1.`Champion`, '')) AS `Partner_In_Glory`
FROM `GoldenPairs` AS T1
LEFT JOIN `table_1_12171145_1` AS T2 ON T1.`Partnership` = T2.col5
AND T2.col0 > T1.`GoldenYear`
WHERE
  T2.col0 IS NULL
ORDER BY
  T1.`GoldenYear`;

nl: My research is focused on identifying prominent 'sporting families' forged through partnership. Which doubles pairs have demonstrated this bond by winning multiple titles together? Please list them by total championships won, so I can analyze the most successful pairings.
sql:
WITH `All_Doubles_Winners` AS (
  SELECT `Mens doubles` AS `partnership` FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Womens doubles` FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Mixed doubles` FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
)
SELECT
  `partnership` AS `Most Successful Doubles Partnership`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total Championships`
FROM `All_Doubles_Winners`
GROUP BY
  `partnership`
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Total Championships` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `All_Doubles_Winners` AS (
  SELECT col3 AS `partnership` FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col4 FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col5 FROM `table_1_12193259_1`
)
SELECT
  `partnership` AS `Most Successful Doubles Partnership`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total Championships`
FROM `All_Doubles_Winners`
GROUP BY
  `partnership`
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Total Championships` DESC;

nl: Show me the first three countries in alphabetical order where it takes more than 250 of their local currency to equal one Euro. For each country, list its currency and indicate if its central bank name begins with 'Bank of'.
sql:
SELECT
  `Country`,
  `Currency`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Central bank` LIKE '`Bank of %`'
    THEN '`Pattern Match`'
    ELSE '`Other`'
  END AS `Bank Name Type`
FROM
  `table_1_1222653_10`
WHERE
  CAST(REPLACE(`1 Euro =`, ',', '') AS REAL) > 250.0
ORDER BY
  `Country` ASC
LIMIT 3;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col0,
  col1,
  CASE
    WHEN col4 LIKE '`Bank of %`'
    THEN '`Pattern Match`'
    ELSE '`Other`'
  END AS `Bank Name Type`
FROM
  `table_1_1222653_10`
WHERE
  CAST(REPLACE(col2, ',', '') AS REAL) > 250.0
ORDER BY
  col0 ASC
LIMIT 3;
reasoning: The user wants the first three results, sorted alphabetically by country. The main filter is on the Euro exchange rate being greater than 250. This question is phrased as a direct request for information.

nl: To develop my doctrine, I must distinguish between enduring partnerships and those who had a brief, intense 'honeymoon period' of wins. Can you sort all multi-title pairs, prioritizing the duos with the longest winning careers first, and then by their total number of championships?
sql:
WITH AllPairs AS (
  SELECT `Year`, `Mens doubles` AS `Pairing`, 'Mens Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Womens doubles` AS `Pairing`, 'Womens Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Mixed doubles` AS `Pairing`, 'Mixed Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
)
SELECT
  `Pairing`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total_Wins`,
  MIN(`Year`) AS `First_Win_Year`,
  MAX(`Year`) AS `Last_Win_Year`,
  MAX(`Year`) - MIN(`Year`) AS `Winning_Longevity_Span`
FROM AllPairs
WHERE `Pairing` IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY
  `Pairing`
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Winning_Longevity_Span` DESC,
  `Total_Wins` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH AllPairs AS (
  SELECT col0, col3 AS `Pairing`, 'Mens Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col4 AS `Pairing`, 'Womens Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col5 AS `Pairing`, 'Mixed Doubles' AS `Category` FROM `table_1_12275551_1`
)
SELECT
  `Pairing`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Total_Wins`,
  MIN(col0) AS `First_Win_Year`,
  MAX(col0) AS `Last_Win_Year`,
  MAX(col0) - MIN(col0) AS `Winning_Longevity_Span`
FROM AllPairs
WHERE `Pairing` IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY
  `Pairing`
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Winning_Longevity_Span` DESC,
  `Total_Wins` DESC;

nl: Which contestants were eliminated despite getting votes from the judges to stay? Rank them by the number of votes they received.
sql:
WITH `JudgeVotes` AS (
  SELECT `Craigs vote` AS `Contestant`, `Eliminated` FROM `table_1_12305325_4`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Arlenes vote`, `Eliminated` FROM `table_1_12305325_4`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Brunos vote`, `Eliminated` FROM `table_1_12305325_4`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Lens vote`, `Eliminated` FROM `table_1_12305325_4`
)
SELECT `Contestant`, COUNT(*) AS `SaveVotes`
FROM `JudgeVotes`
WHERE `Contestant` = `Eliminated` AND `Contestant` IS NOT `N/A`
GROUP BY `Contestant`
ORDER BY `SaveVotes` DESC;

nl: To properly model our 19th-century soldier's escape, we must first identify the most hazardous phase of the operation. Can you calculate the point standard deviation for each of the five survival tasks and rank them from most to least variable? This will serve as our primary risk factor.
sql:
WITH `ParsedScores` AS (
  SELECT
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Shooting`, INSTR(`Shooting`, '(') + 1, INSTR(`Shooting`, ' pts)') - INSTR(`Shooting`, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `ShootingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Fencing`, INSTR(`Fencing`, '(') + 1, INSTR(`Fencing`, ' pts)') - INSTR(`Fencing`, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `FencingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Swimming`, INSTR(`Swimming`, '(') + 1, INSTR(`Swimming`, ' pts)') - INSTR(`Swimming`, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `SwimmingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Riding`, INSTR(`Riding`, '(') + 1, INSTR(`Riding`, ' pts)') - INSTR(`Riding`, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `RidingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(`Running`, INSTR(`Running`, '(') + 1, INSTR(`Running`, ' pts)') - INSTR(`Running`, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `RunningPts`
  FROM `table_1_12407546_2`
)
SELECT `Discipline`, `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)`
FROM (
  SELECT 'Riding' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`RidingPts` * `RidingPts`) - AVG(`RidingPts`) * AVG(`RidingPts`)) AS `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)` FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Fencing' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`FencingPts` * `FencingPts`) - AVG(`FencingPts`) * AVG(`FencingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Swimming' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`SwimmingPts` * `SwimmingPts`) - AVG(`SwimmingPts`) * AVG(`SwimmingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Shooting' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`ShootingPts` * `ShootingPts`) - AVG(`ShootingPts`) * AVG(`ShootingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Running' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`RunningPts` * `RunningPts`) - AVG(`RunningPts`) * AVG(`RunningPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
)
ORDER BY `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `ParsedScores` AS (
  SELECT
    CAST(SUBSTR(col2, INSTR(col2, '(') + 1, INSTR(col2, ' pts)') - INSTR(col2, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `ShootingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col3, INSTR(col3, '(') + 1, INSTR(col3, ' pts)') - INSTR(col3, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `FencingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col4, INSTR(col4, '(') + 1, INSTR(col4, ' pts)') - INSTR(col4, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `SwimmingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, '(') + 1, INSTR(col5, ' pts)') - INSTR(col5, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `RidingPts`,
    CAST(SUBSTR(col6, INSTR(col6, '(') + 1, INSTR(col6, ' pts)') - INSTR(col6, '(') - 1) AS REAL) AS `RunningPts`
  FROM `table_1_12407546_2`
)
SELECT `Discipline`, `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)`
FROM (
  SELECT 'Riding' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`RidingPts` * `RidingPts`) - AVG(`RidingPts`) * AVG(`RidingPts`)) AS `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)` FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Fencing' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`FencingPts` * `FencingPts`) - AVG(`FencingPts`) * AVG(`FencingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Swimming' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`SwimmingPts` * `SwimmingPts`) - AVG(`SwimmingPts`) * AVG(`SwimmingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Shooting' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`ShootingPts` * `ShootingPts`) - AVG(`ShootingPts`) * AVG(`ShootingPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT 'Running' AS `Discipline`, SQRT(AVG(`RunningPts` * `RunningPts`) - AVG(`RunningPts`) * AVG(`RunningPts`)) FROM `ParsedScores`
)
ORDER BY `Risk_Factor (Point Standard Deviation)` DESC;
reasoning: The persona views statistical deviation not as a simple measure of spread, but as a quantifiable 'risk factor' inherent in each 'survival task' of their historical model.
seeding_value: An experimental historian and risk analyst attempting to quantify the 'survival odds' of the modern pentathlon by modeling it after its original concept: a 19th-century cavalry soldier escaping from behind enemy lines. Goals: To identify which of the five disciplines is the most 'lethal' to an athlete's chances of success, and to create a revised scoring system that more accurately reflects the catastrophic risk of failure in each 'survival' task. nl: What are the first 5 examples of theophoric names compounded with 'Yah' that also have a corresponding 'Yahu' form? Please show the English spelling for each name in the pair, sorted by their base Strong's number.
sql:
SELECT DISTINCT
  t1.`English Spelling` AS `Yah_Form`,
  t2.`English Spelling` AS `Yahu_Form`
FROM
  `table_1_1242447_2` AS t1
INNER JOIN
  `table_1_1242447_2` AS t2
ON
  t1.`Strongs #` || 'a' = t2.`Strongs #`
WHERE
  t1.`Strongs Words Compounded` LIKE '%Yah'
  AND t2.`Strongs Words Compounded` LIKE '%Yahu'
ORDER BY
  t1.`Strongs #`
LIMIT
  5;
db_sql:
SELECT DISTINCT
  t1.col4 AS `Yah_Form`,
  t2.col4 AS `Yahu_Form`
FROM
  `table_1_1242447_2` AS t1
INNER JOIN
  `table_1_1242447_2` AS t2
ON
  t1.col0 || 'a' = t2.col0
WHERE
  t1.col3 LIKE '%Yah'
  AND t2.col3 LIKE '%Yahu'
ORDER BY
  t1.col0
LIMIT
  5;
reasoning: This question takes an interrogative form, asking 'What are...'. It breaks down the criteria by first specifying the 'Yah' names and then the condition that they must also have a 'Yahu' form, which mirrors the logic of starting with table t1 and joining t2. It explicitly asks for the English spelling of each name in the pair and includes the sorting and limiting conditions.

nl: To model the league's balance spectrum, I need to see which teams are the most specialized versus the most well-rounded. Can you calculate the disparity between each team's offensive and defensive rank, assign them a playstyle archetype based on that gap, and then order the entire list from most to least lopsided?
sql:
WITH `TeamRanks` AS (
  SELECT
    `Club`,
    `Overall Record`,
    CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Goals For Avg.`, INSTR(`Goals For Avg.`, '(') + 1), 'st)', ''), 'nd)', ''), 'rd)', ''), 'th)', '') AS INTEGER) AS `OffensiveRank`,
    CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`Goals Against Avg.`, INSTR(`Goals Against Avg.`, '(') + 1), 'st)', ''), 'nd)', ''), 'rd)', ''), 'th)', '') AS INTEGER) AS `DefensiveRank`
  FROM `table_1_1246208_5`
)
SELECT
  `Club`,
  `OffensiveRank`,
  `DefensiveRank`,
  ABS(`OffensiveRank` - `DefensiveRank`) AS `RankDisparity`,
  CASE
    WHEN ABS(`OffensiveRank` - `DefensiveRank`) >= 6 THEN
      CASE
        WHEN `OffensiveRank` < `DefensiveRank` THEN 'Glass Cannon'
        ELSE 'The Fortress'
      END
    WHEN ABS(`OffensiveRank` - `DefensiveRank`) <= 1 THEN 'Balanced'
    ELSE
      CASE
        WHEN `OffensiveRank` < `DefensiveRank` THEN 'Offense-Leaning'
        ELSE 'Defense-Leaning'
      END
  END AS `PlaystyleArchetype`
FROM `TeamRanks`
ORDER BY
  `RankDisparity` DESC,
  `PlaystyleArchetype`;

    CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(REPLACE(SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, '(') + 1), 'st)', ''), 'nd)', ''), 'rd)', ''), 'th)', '') AS INTEGER) AS `DefensiveRank`

nl: Isolate the single interval between censuses where the combined population trajectories of the rural versus urban areas moved most dramatically in opposite directions. I need to know the exact period and the scale of this divergence to begin my search for the region's final folklore.
sql:
WITH PopulationChanges AS (
  SELECT
    `Year`,
    LAG(`Year`, 1) OVER (
      ORDER BY
        `Year`
    ) AS `Previous_Year`,
    `Population (Allora)` + `Population (Glengallan)` + `Population (Rosenthal)` AS `Rural_Combined_Pop`,
    LAG(
      `Population (Allora)` + `Population (Glengallan)` + `Population (Rosenthal)`,
      1
    ) OVER (
      ORDER BY
        `Year`
    ) AS `Previous_Rural_Combined_Pop`,
    `Population (Stanthorpe)` + `Population (Warwick)` AS `Urban_Combined_Pop`,
    LAG(
      `Population (Stanthorpe)` + `Population (Warwick)`,
      1
    ) OVER (
      ORDER BY
        `Year`
    ) AS `Previous_Urban_Combined_Pop`
  FROM
    `table_1_12584173_1`
)
SELECT
  `Previous_Year` || '-' || `Year` AS `Period_of_Divergence`,
  `Urban_Combined_Pop` - `Previous_Urban_Combined_Pop` AS `Urban_Center_Growth`,
  `Rural_Combined_Pop` - `Previous_Rural_Combined_Pop` AS `Rural_Shire_Decline`
FROM
  PopulationChanges
WHERE
  `Previous_Year` IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  (`Urban_Combined_Pop` - `Previous_Urban_Combined_Pop`) - (`Rural_Combined_Pop` - `Previous_Rural_Combined_Pop`) DESC
LIMIT 1;

nl: Create a report on ships originating from builders in Jersey City and Cincinnati. The report should include the ship, the builder, and a categorization of its renaming activity: 'Complex Rename History' for multiple changes, 'Original Name Kept' for none, and 'Sold or Renamed Once' for a single change. Sort the report primarily by the builder's name, and secondarily by the ship's name in descending order.
sql:
SELECT
  `Ship`,
  `Builder`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Renamed` LIKE `%;%`
    THEN `Complex Rename History`
    WHEN `Renamed` IS `Not Applicable`
    THEN `Original Name Kept`
    ELSE `Sold or Renamed Once`
  END AS `Naming Status`
FROM
  `table_1_12592074_1`
WHERE
  (`Builder` LIKE `%Jersey City%` OR `Builder` LIKE `%Cincinnati%`)
  AND `Laid down` IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  `Builder` ASC,
  `Ship` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col0,
  col1,
  CASE
    WHEN col3 LIKE '%;%'
    THEN 'Complex Rename History'
    WHEN col3 = 'Not Applicable'
    THEN 'Original Name Kept'
    ELSE 'Sold or Renamed Once'
  END AS `Naming Status`
FROM
  `table_1_12592074_1`
WHERE
  col1 LIKE '%Jersey City%' OR col1 LIKE '%Cincinnati%'
ORDER BY
  col1 ASC,
  col0 DESC;

nl: For the evidentiary record, I need the data aggregated. nl: Can we then classify these teams based on the nature of their internal affiliation? I need to differentiate between, say, a 'Sponsorship: Owner Affiliated' model, where the family business is the sponsor, and an 'Operational: Owner is Driver' model, where the individual is a true owner-operator with outside backing.
sql: SELECT `Team`, `Car(s)`, `Owner(s)`, `Driver(s)`, `Primary Sponsor(s)`, `Rounds`, CASE WHEN `Primary Sponsor(s)` = 'n/a' AND `Owner(s)` = `Driver(s)` THEN 'Self-Funded: Owner is Driver' WHEN `Owner(s)` = `Driver(s)` THEN 'Operational: Owner is Driver' WHEN INSTR(`Primary Sponsor(s)`, SUBSTR(`Owner(s)`, INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Sponsorship: Owner Affiliated' WHEN INSTR(`Primary Sponsor(s)`, SUBSTR(`Crew Chief`, INSTR(`Crew Chief`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Crew Chief`, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Sponsorship: Crew Chief Affiliated' WHEN INSTR(`Driver(s)`, SUBSTR(`Owner(s)`, INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Operational: Family Affiliated' ELSE 'Uncategorized Close-Knit' END AS `Funding_Profile` FROM `table_1_1266602_4` WHERE `Owner(s)` = `Driver(s)` OR (INSTR(`Primary Sponsor(s)`, SUBSTR(`Owner(s)`, INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') > 0) OR (INSTR(`Primary Sponsor(s)`, SUBSTR(`Crew Chief`, INSTR(`Crew Chief`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Crew Chief`, ' ') > 0) OR (INSTR(`Driver(s)`, SUBSTR(`Owner(s)`, INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(`Owner(s)`, ' ') > 0) ORDER BY `Funding_Profile` ASC, `Rounds` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col1, col5, col3, col4, col7, CASE WHEN col4 = 'n/a' AND col5 = col3 THEN 'Self-Funded: Owner is Driver' WHEN col5 = col3 THEN 'Operational: Owner is Driver' WHEN INSTR(col4, SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col5, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Sponsorship: Owner Affiliated' WHEN INSTR(col4, SUBSTR(col6, INSTR(col6, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col6, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Sponsorship: Crew Chief Affiliated' WHEN INSTR(col3, SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col5, ' ') > 0 THEN 'Operational: Family Affiliated' ELSE 'Uncategorized Close-Knit' END AS `Funding_Profile` FROM `table_1_1266602_4` WHERE col5 = col3 OR (INSTR(col4, SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col5, ' ') > 0) OR (INSTR(col4, SUBSTR(col6, INSTR(col6, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col6, ' ') > 0) OR (INSTR(col3, SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, ' ') + 1)) > 0 AND INSTR(col5, ' ') > 0) ORDER BY `Funding_Profile` ASC, col7 DESC;

nl: To build the core dataset for my monograph, I need to map the ebb and flow of viewership against the character's physical journey. Can you generate a full report, ordered by air date, that for each episode with a known location, shows the location itself, its viewership, and the precise percentage of viewership change from the previous episode?
sql:
SELECT
  `Original air date`,
  `Bens location`,
  CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL) AS `Current_Viewers`,
  LAG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY `Original air date`) AS `Previous_Viewers`,
  (CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL), 1, CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL)) OVER (ORDER BY `Original air date`)) * 100.0 / LAG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL), 1, CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL)) OVER (ORDER BY `Original air date`) AS `Viewership_Percent_Change`
FROM
  `table_1_12722302_2`
WHERE
  `Bens location` IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  `Original air date`;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col5,
  col4,
  CAST(col6 AS REAL) AS `Current_Viewers`,
  LAG(CAST(col6 AS REAL), 1, 0) OVER (ORDER BY col5) AS `Previous_Viewers`,
  (CAST(col6 AS REAL) - LAG(CAST(col6 AS REAL), 1, CAST(col6 AS REAL)) OVER (ORDER BY col5)) * 100.0 / LAG(CAST(col6 AS REAL), 1, CAST(col6 AS REAL)) OVER (ORDER BY col5) AS `Viewership_Percent_Change`
FROM
  `table_1_12722302_2`
WHERE
  col4 IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY
  col5;
reasoning: This is the all-encompassing question that captures the full dataset needed for their research. It frames the entire query in the language of their 'fictional psychogeography' hypothesis, linking location, time, and audience reaction together.

Goals: To publish a monograph proving that episodes with explicitly named, real-world towns (the 'anchors') create a stronger narrative gravity that holds viewer attention, while episodes in nebulous or 'N/A' locations cause a measurable drop in audience connection and ratings. Example Queries: What is the average viewership for episodes where 'Bens location' is a specific town versus episodes where it is listed as 'N/A'? Which writer is most frequently associated with episodes where the location is 'N/A', and how do their viewership numbers compare to other writers? Show me the sequence of locations Ben visits, ordered by air date, and include the percentage change in viewership between each consecutive episode.

nl: Show me the writers who have written more than one episode for which we have viewership data. For each writer, display their total number of episodes and classify them as 'Prolific & Popular' if their average viewership is over 1.8 million, otherwise as 'Prolific'. Please sort the results by the episode count from most to least.
sql:
SELECT
  `Written by`,
  COUNT(*) AS `Episode_Count`,
  CASE
    WHEN AVG(CAST(`U.S. viewers (million)` AS REAL)) > 1.8 THEN `Prolific & Popular`
    ELSE `Prolific`
  END AS `Writer_Status`
FROM
  `table_1_12722302_3`
WHERE
  `U.S. viewers (million)` <> `N/A`
GROUP BY
  `Written by`
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Episode_Count` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col4,
  COUNT(*) AS `Episode_Count`,
  CASE
    WHEN AVG(col7 * 1.0) > 1.8 THEN 'Prolific & Popular'
    ELSE 'Prolific'
  END AS `Writer_Status`
FROM
  `table_1_12722302_3`
WHERE
  col7 <> 'N/A'
GROUP BY
  col4
HAVING
  COUNT(*) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Episode_Count` DESC;
db_result: [('william schmidt', 2, 'Prolific'), ('tracy tormé', 2, 'Prolific'), ('dawn prestwich & nicole yorkin', 2, 'Prolific'), ('daniel knauf', 2, 'Prolific')]
reasoning: This reasoning parses the SQL query into its core components. It identifies the target group (writers with more than one episode), the calculations (counting episodes, averaging viewers), the conditional logic for status assignment ('Prolific' vs. 'Prolific & Popular' based on a 1.8M viewer threshold), the data filtering (excluding 'N/A' viewers), and the final sorting order (descending by episode count). This detailed breakdown ensures all query constraints are captured in the natural language question.

nl: From this 2007 artifact, which of the multi-core processors represented the primary economic lever for market adoption? I need a list of the models ranked by their 'bang-for-the-buck'—let's define that as total L3 cache multiplied by core count, divided by price—to see which one offered the most power per dollar.
sql: SELECT `Model Number`, `Cores`, `L3`, `Price ( USD )`, (CAST(REPLACE(`L3`, ' MB', '') AS REAL) * `Cores`) / CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(`Price ( USD )`, '$', ''), ',', '') AS REAL) AS `Cache_Core_per_Dollar` FROM `table_1_12740151_8` WHERE `Cores` > 1 ORDER BY `Cache_Core_per_Dollar` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, col6, col3, col12, (CAST(REPLACE(col3, ' MB', '') AS REAL) * col6) / CAST(REPLACE(REPLACE(col12, '$', ''), ',', '') AS REAL) AS `Cache_Core_per_Dollar` FROM `table_1_12740151_8` WHERE col6 > 1 ORDER BY `Cache_Core_per_Dollar` DESC;
reasoning: The persona is trying to identify the 'sweet spot' in the product line. This question uses their specific lens ('historical artifact', 'economic levers') and frames the complex SQL calculation as a simple 'bang-for-the-buck' analysis to find the product that could have sparked mainstream adoption in their alternate timeline.
seeding_value: A speculative historian writing a novel about an alternate reality where the Itanium architecture succeeded, who uses this data as a 'historical artifact' to understand the economic levers that could have led to its dominance. Goals: To analyze the 2007 pricing strategy for this specific family of processors, looking for the 'sweet spot' of performance vs. cost that could have propelled Itanium into the mainstream consumer market in their fictional timeline. nl: Give me the full diagnostic on every scorer from that season. I need to see their name, the raw count of competitions they netted in, their assigned 'Scoring Profile', and the final Versatility Ratio. Make sure the output prioritizes the players with the highest competition count first.
sql: SELECT `Player`, (`League` > 0) + (`Scottish Cup` > 0) + (`League Cup` > 0) + (`Challenge Cup` > 0) AS `Competitions_Scored_In`, CASE WHEN (`League` > 0) + (`Scottish Cup` > 0) + (`League Cup` > 0) + (`Challenge Cup` > 0) = 1 THEN 'Specialist' WHEN (`League` > 0) + (`Scottish Cup` > 0) + (`League Cup` > 0) + (`Challenge Cup` > 0) > 2 THEN 'Poly-Scorer' ELSE 'Versatile' END AS `Scoring_Profile`, CAST((`League` > 0) + (`Scottish Cup` > 0) + (`League Cup` > 0) + (`Challenge Cup` > 0) AS REAL) / `Total` AS `Versatility_Ratio` FROM `table_1_12755786_8` WHERE `Total` > 0 ORDER BY `Competitions_Scored_In` DESC, `Versatility_Ratio` DESC;
db_sql: SELECT col0, (col1 > 0) + (col2 > 0) + (col3 > 0) + (col4 > 0) AS `Competitions_Scored_In`, CASE WHEN (col1 > 0) + (col2 > 0) + (col3 > 0) + (col4 > 0) = 1 THEN 'Specialist' WHEN (col1 > 0) + (col2 > 0) + (col3 > 0) + (col4 > 0) > 2 THEN 'Poly-Scorer' ELSE 'Versatile' END AS `Scoring_Profile`, CAST((col1 > 0) + (col2 > 0) + (col3 > 0) + (col4 > 0) AS REAL) / col5 AS `Versatility_Ratio` FROM `table_1_12755786_8` WHERE col5 > 0 ORDER BY `Competitions_Scored_In` DESC, `Versatility_Ratio` DESC;

nl: I'm looking at years with unusually long operational windows, specifically those that stayed open after the first week of April. Which of these late-season years had the highest daily traffic intensity? I need to see if the most intense, prolonged disturbances correlate with our collar data on delayed migration to the calving grounds.
sql:
WITH `yearly_disturbance_metrics` AS (
  SELECT
    `Year`,
    `Road Closed`,
    (
      CAST(`Year` AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
        WHEN `Road Closed` LIKE 'Mar%' THEN '03'
        WHEN `Road Closed` LIKE 'Apr%' THEN '04'
      END || '-' || printf(
        '%02d',
        SUBSTR(`Road Closed`, INSTR(`Road Closed`, ' ') + 1)
      )
    ) AS `iso_close_date`,
    CAST(`Number of Truck Loads North` AS REAL) / (
      JULIANDAY(
        CAST(`Year` AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
          WHEN `Road Closed` LIKE 'Mar%' THEN '03'
          WHEN `Road Closed` LIKE 'Apr%' THEN '04'
        END || '-' || printf(
          '%02d',
          SUBSTR(`Road Closed`, INSTR(`Road Closed`, ' ') + 1)
        )
      ) - JULIANDAY(
        CAST(`Year` AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
          WHEN `Road Opened` LIKE 'Jan%' THEN '01'
          WHEN `Road Opened` LIKE 'Feb%' THEN '02'
        END || '-' || printf(
          '%02d',
          SUBSTR(`Road Opened`, INSTR(`Road Opened`, ' ') + 1)
        )
      )
    ) AS `avg_daily_trucks`
  FROM `table_1_12791809_1`
)
SELECT
  `Year`,
  `Road Closed`,
  `avg_daily_trucks` AS `Average Daily Truck Loads`
FROM `yearly_disturbance_metrics`
WHERE
  `iso_close_date` > CAST(`Year` AS TEXT) || '-04-09'
ORDER BY
  `avg_daily_trucks` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `yearly_disturbance_metrics` AS (
  SELECT
    col0,
    col2,
    (
      CAST(col0 AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
        WHEN col2 LIKE 'Mar%' THEN '03'
        WHEN col2 LIKE 'Apr%' THEN '04'
      END || '-' || printf(
        '%02d',
        SUBSTR(col2, INSTR(col2, ' ') + 1)
      )
    ) AS `iso_close_date`,
    CAST(col5 AS REAL) / (
      JULIANDAY(
        CAST(col0 AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
          WHEN col2 LIKE 'Mar%' THEN '03'
          WHEN col2 LIKE 'Apr%' THEN '04'
        END || '-' || printf(
          '%02d',
          SUBSTR(col2, INSTR(col2, ' ') + 1)
        )
      ) - JULIANDAY(
        CAST(col0 AS TEXT) || '-' || CASE
          WHEN col1 LIKE 'Jan%' THEN '01'
          WHEN col1 LIKE 'Feb%' THEN '02'
        END || '-' || printf(
          '%02d',
          SUBSTR(col1, INSTR(col1, ' ') + 1)
        )
      )
    ) AS `avg_daily_trucks`
  FROM `table_1_12791809_1`
)
SELECT
  col0,
  col2,
  `avg_daily_trucks` AS `Average Daily Truck Loads`
FROM `yearly_disturbance_metrics`
WHERE
  `iso_close_date` > CAST(col0 AS TEXT) || '-04-09'
ORDER BY
  `avg_daily_trucks` DESC;

nl: Which Little League programs represent our ideal model for a long-term community fabric? I need a summary of teams that have won multiple times, ranked by the longevity of their winning era, that also includes their total championship count and a timeline of those victories.
sql:
WITH `UnpivotedTeams` AS (
  SELECT `Year`, `Connecticut` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Maine` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Massachusetts` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `New Hampshire` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Rhode Island` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT `Year`, `Vermont` AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
)
SELECT
  `Team`,
  MAX(`Year`) - MIN(`Year`) AS `Championship_Longevity_Span`,
  COUNT(`Year`) AS `Total_Championships`,
  GROUP_CONCAT(`Year`, `, `) AS `Winning_Years`
FROM `UnpivotedTeams`
GROUP BY
  `Team`
HAVING
  COUNT(`Year`) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Championship_Longevity_Span` DESC,
  `Total_Championships` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `UnpivotedTeams` AS (
  SELECT col0, col1 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col2 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col3 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col4 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col5 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT col0, col6 AS `Team` FROM `table_1_13011547_1`
)
SELECT
  `Team`,
  MAX(col0) - MIN(col0) AS `Championship_Longevity_Span`,
  COUNT(col0) AS `Total_Championships`,
  GROUP_CONCAT(col0, ', ') AS `Winning_Years`
FROM `UnpivotedTeams`
GROUP BY
  `Team`
HAVING
  COUNT(col0) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Championship_Longevity_Span` DESC,
  `Total_Championships` DESC;

nl: To fully illustrate the contingent nature of this championship, please provide a comparative table. For the top two teams, show their club name, their actual points, their points difference, and their hypothetical points if Featherstone had one more, then sort the output to reveal the new champion under this alternate timeline.
sql:
SELECT
  `Club`,
  `Points` AS `Original Points`,
  (`Pts For` - `Pts Agst`) AS `Points Difference`,
  CASE
    WHEN `Club` = `Featherstone Rovers`
    THEN `Points` + 1
    ELSE `Points`
  END AS `Hypothetical Points`
FROM `table_1_13015539_1`
WHERE
  `Position` <= 2
ORDER BY
  `Hypothetical Points` DESC,
  `Points Difference` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  col1,
  col9 AS `Original Points`,
  (col6 - col7) AS `Points Difference`,
  CASE
    WHEN col1 = 'Featherstone Rovers'
    THEN col9 + 1
    ELSE col9
  END AS `Hypothetical Points`
FROM `table_1_13015539_1`
WHERE
  col0 <= 2
ORDER BY
  `Hypothetical Points` DESC,
  `Points Difference` DESC;
reasoning: This is the culminating question, asking for a complete dataset that juxtaposes reality with the hypothetical, sorted to prove his point. It encapsulates the entire SQL query and the persona's ultimate goal of demonstrating 'The Fragility of Victory'.

Goals: To use the 2007 National League Two table as a prime example for his thesis on 'The Fragility of Victory,' demonstrating how the championship was decided not by dominance, but by a single, potentially random, bonus point. Example Queries: Calculate a 'Grit Score' for each team by finding the ratio of Bonus Points to Losses, identifying teams that consistently fought hard in defeat. If Featherstone Rovers had secured one more bonus point, how would the final top position have changed based on points difference? Identify the teams with the highest number of bonus points relative to their final league position to find the most 'unlucky' competitors of the season.

nl: To build out my 'Illinois '04 Pivot Point Tour', can you pull a list of our key stops? UNION ALL
SELECT `County`, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT `County`, `Blue Stronghold` AS `Tour Stop Type`, `Kerry%` AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(`Kerry%`, `%`, ``) AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1)
UNION ALL
SELECT `County`, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT `County`, `Red Stronghold` AS `Tour Stop Type`, `Bush%` AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(`Bush%`, `%`, ``) AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1)
UNION ALL
SELECT `County`, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT `County`, `Maverick County` AS `Tour Stop Type`, `Others%` AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(`Others%`, `%`, ``) AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1);

SELECT col0, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT col0, 'Battleground' AS `Tour Stop Type`, printf('%.1f%% Margin', ABS(CAST(REPLACE(col1, '%', '') AS REAL) - CAST(REPLACE(col3, '%', '') AS REAL))) AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY ABS(CAST(REPLACE(col1, '%', '') AS REAL) - CAST(REPLACE(col3, '%', '') AS REAL)) ASC LIMIT 3)
UNION ALL
SELECT col0, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT col0, 'Blue Stronghold' AS `Tour Stop Type`, col1 AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(col1, '%', '') AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1)
UNION ALL
SELECT col0, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT col0, 'Red Stronghold' AS `Tour Stop Type`, col3 AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(col3, '%', '') AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1)

SELECT col0, `Tour Stop Type`, `Defining Metric` FROM (SELECT col0, 'Maverick County' AS `Tour Stop Type`, col5 AS `Defining Metric` FROM `table_1_1302886_1` ORDER BY CAST(REPLACE(col5, '%', '') AS REAL) DESC LIMIT 1);

nl: Which ensembles exhibit a strong 'runner-up resilience' profile, defined as having more silver medals than gold? Please rank these programs by their 'Breakthrough Potential Ratio'—calculated as their combined silver and bronze medals divided by their gold medals plus one—from highest to lowest.
sql: SELECT `Ensemble`, `Gold Medals`, `Silver Medals`, `Bronze Medals`, (CAST(`Silver Medals` AS REAL) + `Bronze Medals`) / (`Gold Medals` + 1.0) AS `Breakthrough_Potential_Ratio` FROM `table_1_1305623_20` WHERE `Silver Medals` > `Gold Medals` ORDER BY `Breakthrough_Potential_Ratio` DESC;

reasoning: The persona frames their request using their core theory, viewing a surplus of silver medals not as failure, but as 'runner-up resilience'. The calculated ratio is their proprietary, quantitative measure of this latent potential.

nl: For my analysis of the Kōhaku's principal players, I require a comprehensive performance chronology. Please compile a record for every individual who has graced the stage as a host on more than one occasion, detailing for each appearance the year, the faction they represented, the outcome, and a running tally of their career victories.
sql:
WITH HostAppearances AS (
  SELECT
    `Red Team Host` AS `Host`,
    `Red` AS `Team`,
    `Date`,
    `Winning Team`
  FROM `table_1_1315616_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT
    `White Team Host` AS `Host`,
    `White` AS `Team`,
    `Date`,
    `Winning Team`
  FROM `table_1_1315616_1`
)
SELECT
  ha.`Host` AS `Recurring Actor`,
  SUBSTR(ha.`Date`, -4) AS `Performance Year`,
  ha.`Team` AS `Role`,
  CASE WHEN ha.`Team` = ha.`Winning Team` THEN `Win` ELSE `Loss` END AS `Outcome`,
  SUM(CASE WHEN ha.`Team` = ha.`Winning Team` THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) OVER (PARTITION BY ha.`Host` ORDER BY ha.`Date`) AS `Career Wins`,
  ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY ha.`Host` ORDER BY ha.`Date`) AS `Appearance #`
FROM HostAppearances AS ha
WHERE
  ha.`Host` IN (
    SELECT
      `Host`
    FROM HostAppearances
    GROUP BY
      `Host`
    HAVING
      COUNT(*) > 1
  )
ORDER BY
  `Recurring Actor`,
  `Performance Year`;
db_sql:
WITH HostAppearances AS (
  SELECT
    col2 AS `Host`,
    'Red' AS `Team`,
    col1,
    col5
  FROM `table_1_1315616_1`
  UNION ALL
  SELECT
    col3 AS `Host`,
    'White' AS `Team`,
    col1,
    col5
  FROM `table_1_1315616_1`
)
SELECT
  ha.`Host` AS `Recurring Actor`,
  SUBSTR(ha.col1, -4) AS `Performance Year`,
  ha.`Team` AS `Role`,
  CASE WHEN ha.`Team` = ha.col5 THEN 'Win' ELSE 'Loss' END AS `Outcome`,
  SUM(CASE WHEN ha.`Team` = ha.col5 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) OVER (PARTITION BY ha.`Host` ORDER BY ha.col1) AS `Career Wins`,
  ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY ha.`Host` ORDER BY ha.col1) AS `Appearance #`
FROM HostAppearances AS ha
WHERE
  ha.`Host` IN (
    SELECT
      `Host`
    FROM HostAppearances
    GROUP BY
      `Host`
    HAVING
      COUNT(*) > 1
  )
ORDER BY
  `Recurring Actor`,
  `Performance Year`;

nl: Can you give me a quantitative breakdown of the 2001 release landscape? I need to see the total number of notable titles for each major platform category—that is, 6th gen consoles, 5th gen consoles, PC, and handhelds—ordered from most to least prolific.
sql:
SELECT
  CASE
    WHEN `6th Gen` != 'N/A' THEN '6th Gen Console'
    WHEN `Windows` != 'N/A' THEN 'PC'
    WHEN `5th Gen` != 'N/A' THEN '5th Gen Console'

nl: How many times did the Seahawks play against each opponent they faced more than once in the 1987 season? List the opponents in descending alphabetical order and ignore any games that were cancelled due to the player's strike.
sql:
SELECT
  `Opponent` AS `Recurring_Opponent`,
  COUNT(`Week`)
FROM
  `table_1_13258806_2`
WHERE
  `Result` IS NOT `Cancelled due to player's strike`
GROUP BY
  `Opponent`
HAVING
  COUNT(`Week`) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Opponent` DESC;
db_sql:
SELECT
  REPLACE(col2, 'at ', '') AS `Recurring_Opponent`,
  COUNT(col0)
FROM
  `table_1_13258806_2`
WHERE
  col3 <> "Cancelled due to player's strike"
GROUP BY
  `Recurring_Opponent`
HAVING
  COUNT(col0) > 1
ORDER BY
  `Recurring_Opponent`;
reasoning: This version frames the core request around the count ('How many times...'), directly addressing the COUNT aggregation. It then specifies the conditions for which opponents to include (faced more than once) and how to present them (descending order, ignoring cancellations), mapping clearly to the HAVING, ORDER BY, and WHERE clauses.

FROM
  `table_1_13259034_2` AS `T1`
WHERE

SELECT

nl: Let's find the episodes with the most significant vibrational misalignment. Show me a list of all episodes that were aired out of production order, but rank them starting with the ones that were shifted the most from their original place in the sequence.
sql:
WITH OrderedEpisodes AS (
  SELECT
    `Title`,
    `Production code`,
    `Original air date`,
    `U.S. viewers (millions)`,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY `Original air date`) AS AiringSequence,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY `Production code`) AS ProductionSequence
  FROM
    `table_1_13301516_1`
)
SELECT
  `Title`,
  `Production code`,
  `Original air date`,
  `U.S. viewers (millions)`,
  (ProductionSequence - AiringSequence) AS `Rhythmic Dissonance`
FROM
  OrderedEpisodes
WHERE
  `Rhythmic Dissonance` != 0
ORDER BY
  ABS(`Rhythmic Dissonance`) DESC;
db_sql:
WITH OrderedEpisodes AS (
  SELECT
    col2,
    col6,
    col5,
    col7,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY col5) AS AiringSequence,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY col6) AS ProductionSequence
  FROM
    `table_1_13301516_1`
)
SELECT
  col2,
  col6,
  col5,
  col7,
  (ProductionSequence - AiringSequence) AS `Rhythmic Dissonance`
FROM
  OrderedEpisodes
WHERE
  `Rhythmic Dissonance` != 0
ORDER BY
  ABS(`Rhythmic Dissonance`) DESC;
reasoning: This question focuses on the magnitude of the disruption, which the persona calls 'vibrational misalignment'. The SQL query's `ORDER BY ABS(Rhythmic Dissonance) DESC` clause directly addresses this by sorting the results to show the most 'out of tune' episodes first.

nl: Can you show me a list of all incumbents and their parties, grouped by seniority? Let's call those elected in 2001 or later the 'Freshman Class'. For the others, let's call those elected before 1995 'Senior Caucus' and those elected from 1995 through 2000 'Junior Caucus', but only if their party has more than one member listed. Please arrange the list from newest to oldest member.
sql:
WITH `IncumbentEras` AS (
  SELECT `Incumbent`, `Party`, `First elected` AS `Year`, `Result`
  FROM `table_1_1341395_22`
  WHERE `Result` IS NOT NULL
)
SELECT
  s1.`Incumbent`, s1.`Party`,
  CASE WHEN s1.`Year` < 1995 THEN 'Senior Caucus' ELSE 'Junior Caucus' END AS `Status`
FROM `IncumbentEras` AS `s1`
LEFT JOIN `IncumbentEras` AS `s2`
  ON s1.`Party` = s2.`Party`
WHERE
  s1.`Year` < 2001 AND s1.`Incumbent` <> s2.`Incumbent`
GROUP BY s1.`Incumbent`, s1.`Party`, s1.`Year`
UNION ALL
SELECT
  `Incumbent`, `Party`, 'Freshman Class' AS `Status`
FROM `IncumbentEras` AS `s3`
WHERE
  s3.`Year` >= 2001
ORDER BY `Year` DESC;
db_sql:
WITH `IncumbentEras` AS (
  SELECT
    col1,
    col2,
    col3 AS `Year`,
    col4
  FROM `table_1_1341395_22`
  WHERE
    col4 IS NOT NULL
)
SELECT
  s1.col1,
  s1.col2,
  s1.`Year`,
  CASE WHEN s1.`Year` < 1995 THEN 'Senior Caucus' ELSE 'Junior Caucus' END AS `Status`
FROM `IncumbentEras` AS `s1`
LEFT JOIN `IncumbentEras` AS `s2` ON s1.col2 = s2.col2
WHERE
  s1.`Year` < 2001 AND s1.col1 <> s2.col1
GROUP BY
  s1.col1,
  s1.col2,
  s1.`Year`
UNION ALL
SELECT
  col1,
  col2,
  `Year`,
  'Freshman Class' AS `Status`
FROM `IncumbentEras` AS `s3`
WHERE
  s3.`Year` >= 2001
ORDER BY
  `Year` DESC;

nl: For my study on the 'ritual of opposition' in the 2000 Massachusetts elections, I need to identify the Republican sacrificial lambs. db_sql: SELECT col0, TRIM(SUBSTR(SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, '%') + 1), 1, INSTR(SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, '%') + 1), '(R)') - 1)) AS `Republican Challenger`, CAST(REPLACE(TRIM(SUBSTR(col5, INSTR(col5, '(R)') + 3)), '%', '') AS REAL) AS `Vote Percentage`, col1 AS `Incumbent Opponent`, 2000 - col3 AS `Incumbent Seniority (Years)` FROM `table_1_1341423_21` WHERE col5 LIKE '%(R)%' ORDER BY `Incumbent Seniority (Years)` DESC;

It precisely asks for all the data points extracted by the SQL query and justifies the sorting order based on the persona's analytical interest in 'entrenched figures'.

WITH `ChallengerData` AS (
  SELECT
    `District`,
    `Incumbent`,
    `Elected`,
    TRIM(SUBSTR(`Opponent`, INSTR(`Opponent`, '%') + 1)) AS `ChallengerInfo`
  FROM `table_1_1341568_34`
)
SELECT
  `District`,
  `Incumbent`,
  (1990 - `Elected`) AS `Incumbent Tenure (Years)`,
  SUBSTR(`ChallengerInfo`, 1, INSTR(`ChallengerInfo`, ' (') - 1) AS `Challenger`,
  CAST(REPLACE(SUBSTR(`ChallengerInfo`, INSTR(`ChallengerInfo`, ') ') + 2), '%', '') AS REAL) AS `Challenger Vote Share (%)`
FROM `ChallengerData`
ORDER BY `Incumbent Tenure (Years)` DESC;

WITH `NumerologyData` AS (
  SELECT
    `Incumbent`,
    `District`,
    CASE
      WHEN `Candidates` LIKE '%Unopposed%' THEN 100.0
      ELSE ROUND((2 * CAST(TRIM(SUBSTR(`Candidates`, INSTR(`Candidates`, `)`) + 1, INSTR(`Candidates`, `%`) - INSTR(`Candidates`, `)`))) AS REAL)) - 100, 1)
    END AS `VictoryMargin`
  FROM
    `table_1_1341577_36`
)
SELECT
  `Incumbent`,
  `District`,
  `VictoryMargin` AS `KarmicMargin`,
  CASE
    WHEN `VictoryMargin` = 100.0 THEN 'Unstable Omen (Hubris Risk)'
    WHEN `VictoryMargin` > 60.0 THEN 'Cosmic Mandate (Path to Power)'
    WHEN `VictoryMargin` < 15.0 THEN 'Dissonant Friction (Future Turmoil)'
    ELSE 'Balanced Path (Steady Karma)'
  END AS `DestinyClue`
FROM
  `NumerologyData`
ORDER BY
  `VictoryMargin` DESC;
